2130
01:37:43,680 --> 01:37:46,619
is limited by how you power the thing

2131
01:37:46,619 --> 01:37:48,539
and get the data off of it.

2132
01:37:48,539 --> 01:37:50,880
And at the end of the day, fundamentally,

2133
01:37:50,880 --> 01:37:52,859
if you look at a human body,

2134
01:37:52,859 --> 01:37:55,710
we're essentially a bag of salt water,

2135
01:37:55,710 --> 01:37:57,810
with some interesting
proteins and chemicals,

2136
01:37:57,810 --> 01:38:01,980
but it's mostly salt water
that's very, very well

2137
01:38:01,979 --> 01:38:04,772
temperature-regulated
at 37 degrees Celsius.

2138
01:38:05,939 --> 01:38:08,849
And we'll get into how, and later,

2139
01:38:08,850 --> 01:38:11,070
why that's an extremely harsh environment

2140
01:38:11,069 --> 01:38:12,539
for any electronics to survive,

2141
01:38:12,539 --> 01:38:17,039
as I'm sure you've experienced
or maybe not experienced

2142
01:38:17,039 --> 01:38:20,130
dropping cell phone in a
salt water in an ocean.

2143
01:38:20,130 --> 01:38:22,180
It will instantly kill the device, right?

2144
01:38:23,670 --> 01:38:26,069
But anyways, just in general,

2145
01:38:26,069 --> 01:38:28,319
electromagnetic waves don't penetrate

2146
01:38:28,319 --> 01:38:29,853
through this environment well.

2147
01:38:30,810 --> 01:38:34,548
And just the speed of
light, it is what it is.

2148
01:38:34,547 --> 01:38:35,819
We can't change it.

2149
01:38:35,819 --> 01:38:40,819
And based on the wavelength
at which you are interfacing

2150
01:38:41,850 --> 01:38:44,833
with the device, the device
just needs to be big.

2151
01:38:44,832 --> 01:38:47,069
Like these inductors
needs to be quite big.

2152
01:38:47,069 --> 01:38:49,829
And the general good rule of thumb is that

2153
01:38:49,829 --> 01:38:53,460
you want the wavefront to
be roughly on the order

2154
01:38:53,460 --> 01:38:56,159
of the size of the thing
that you're interfacing with.

2155
01:38:56,159 --> 01:39:00,630
So an implantable system that is around

2156
01:39:00,630 --> 01:39:04,590
10 to 100 micron in dimension in a volume,

2157
01:39:04,590 --> 01:39:05,940
which is about the size of a neuron

2158
01:39:05,939 --> 01:39:08,342
that you see in a human body,

2159
01:39:10,350 --> 01:39:12,960
you would have to operate at
like hundreds of gigahertz,

2160
01:39:12,960 --> 01:39:15,539
which number one, not only is it difficult

2161
01:39:15,539 --> 01:39:18,840
to build electronics operating
at those frequencies,

2162
01:39:18,840 --> 01:39:21,420
but also, the body just attenuates that

2163
01:39:21,420 --> 01:39:23,760
very, very significantly.

2164
01:39:23,760 --> 01:39:27,989
So the interesting kind of
insight of this ultrasound

2165
01:39:27,989 --> 01:39:31,739
was the fact that ultrasound just travels

2166
01:39:31,739 --> 01:39:34,679
a lot more effectively
in the human body tissue

2167
01:39:34,680 --> 01:39:36,960
compared to electromagnetic waves.

2168
01:39:36,960 --> 01:39:39,212
And this is something that you encounter,

2169
01:39:40,199 --> 01:39:42,720
and I'm sure most people have encountered

2170
01:39:42,720 --> 01:39:46,170
in their lives when you go to hospitals

2171
01:39:46,170 --> 01:39:50,703
that are medical ultrasound
sonograph, right?

2172
01:39:52,079 --> 01:39:55,680
And they go into very, very deep depth

2173
01:39:55,680 --> 01:39:58,560
without attenuating
too much of the signal.

2174
01:39:58,560 --> 01:40:03,560
So all in all, ultrasound,
the fact that it travels

2175
01:40:03,989 --> 01:40:05,639
through the body extremely well

2176
01:40:05,640 --> 01:40:08,250
and the mechanism to which
it travels to the body

2177
01:40:08,250 --> 01:40:11,220
really well is that just the
wavefront is very different.

2178
01:40:11,220 --> 01:40:15,210
Its electromagnetic waves are transverse,

2179
01:40:15,210 --> 01:40:17,760
whereas ultrasound waves are compressive.

2180
01:40:17,760 --> 01:40:19,560
So it's just a completely different mode

2181
01:40:19,560 --> 01:40:23,520
of wavefront propagation,

2182
01:40:23,520 --> 01:40:25,740
and as well as speed of sound

2183
01:40:25,739 --> 01:40:30,029
is orders and orders of magnitude
less than speed of light,

2184
01:40:30,029 --> 01:40:33,929
which means that even at 10
megahertz ultrasound wave,

2185
01:40:33,930 --> 01:40:37,770
your wavefront ultimately is
a very, very small wavelength.

2186
01:40:37,770 --> 01:40:39,960
So if you're talking about interfacing

2187
01:40:39,960 --> 01:40:43,922
with the 10 micron or 100
micron type structure,

2188
01:40:45,539 --> 01:40:49,350
you would have 150 micron
wavefront at 10 megahertz.

2189
01:40:49,350 --> 01:40:52,320
And building electronics
at those frequencies

2190
01:40:52,319 --> 01:40:53,340
are much, much, much easier

2191
01:40:53,340 --> 01:40:55,380
and they're a lot more efficient.

2192
01:40:55,380 --> 01:41:00,380
So the basic idea kind of was
born out of using ultrasound

2193
01:41:01,710 --> 01:41:03,630
as a mechanism for powering the device,

2194
01:41:03,630 --> 01:41:05,970
and then also getting data back.

2195
01:41:05,970 --> 01:41:08,850
So now the question is, how
do you get the data back?

2196
01:41:08,850 --> 01:41:10,440
The mechanism to which we landed on

2197
01:41:10,439 --> 01:41:12,659
is what's called backscattering.

2198
01:41:12,659 --> 01:41:16,170
This is actually something
that is very common

2199
01:41:16,170 --> 01:41:18,659
and that we interface
on a day-to-day basis

2200
01:41:18,659 --> 01:41:22,649
with our RFID cards, our
radio frequency ID tag,

2201
01:41:22,649 --> 01:41:27,649
where there's actually rarely,
in your ID, a battery inside.

2202
01:41:28,859 --> 01:41:32,639
There's an antenna and
there's some sort of coil

2203
01:41:32,640 --> 01:41:37,079
that has your serial identification ID

2204
01:41:37,079 --> 01:41:38,279
and then there's an external device

2205
01:41:38,279 --> 01:41:41,759
called a reader that
then sends a wavefront,

2206
01:41:41,760 --> 01:41:44,010
and then you reflect back that wavefront

2207
01:41:44,010 --> 01:41:46,710
with some sort of modulation
that's unique to your ID.

2208
01:41:47,640 --> 01:41:50,640
That's what's called
backscattering, fundamentally.

2209
01:41:50,640 --> 01:41:52,500
So the tag itself actually

2210
01:41:52,500 --> 01:41:54,930
doesn't have to consume that much energy.

2211
01:41:54,930 --> 01:41:58,560
And that was a mechanism to which we were

2212
01:41:58,560 --> 01:42:00,180
kind of thinking about
sending the data back.

2213
01:42:00,180 --> 01:42:04,260
So when you have an external
ultrasonic transducer

2214
01:42:04,260 --> 01:42:07,470
that's sending ultrasonic
wave to your implant,

2215
01:42:07,470 --> 01:42:09,000
