03:54:38,430 --> 03:54:40,353
for a neurosurgeon of humility,

4990
03:54:41,340 --> 03:54:44,880
which I think indicates
that it's not as common

4991
03:54:44,879 --> 03:54:46,469
as perhaps in other professions,

4992
03:54:46,469 --> 03:54:49,889
'cause there is a kind of gigantic

4993
03:54:49,889 --> 03:54:52,289
sort of heroic aspect to neurosurgery,

4994
03:54:52,290 --> 03:54:54,930
and I think it gets to
people's head a little bit.

4995
03:54:54,930 --> 03:54:55,920
- Yeah.

4996
03:54:55,920 --> 03:55:00,870
Well, I think that allows me to play well

4997
03:55:00,870 --> 03:55:02,763
at an Elon company.

4998
03:55:03,719 --> 03:55:06,689
Because Elon, one of his strengths,

4999
03:55:06,690 --> 03:55:11,460
I think, is to just instantly see through

5000
03:55:11,459 --> 03:55:13,829
fallacy from authority.

5001
03:55:13,829 --> 03:55:15,756
So nobody walks into a
room that he's in and says,

5002
03:55:15,756 --> 03:55:18,629
"Well, goddamn it, you have to trust me.

5003
03:55:18,629 --> 03:55:22,136
I'm the guy that built the
last 10 rockets or something."

5004
03:55:22,137 --> 03:55:23,550
And he says, "Well, you did it wrong

5005
03:55:23,549 --> 03:55:25,349
and we can do it better."

5006
03:55:25,350 --> 03:55:27,809
Or, "I'm the guy that kept Ford

5007
03:55:27,809 --> 03:55:29,309
alive for the last 50 years.

5008
03:55:29,309 --> 03:55:30,840
You listen to me on how to build cars."

5009
03:55:30,840 --> 03:55:32,972
And he says no.

5010
03:55:34,406 --> 03:55:36,179
And so you don't walk
into a room that he's in

5011
03:55:36,180 --> 03:55:37,620
and say, "Well, I'm a neurosurgeon.

5012
03:55:37,620 --> 03:55:39,600
Let me tell you how to do it."

5013
03:55:39,600 --> 03:55:43,530
He's gonna say, "Well, I'm a
human being that has a brain.

5014
03:55:43,530 --> 03:55:45,960
I can think from first principles myself,

5015
03:55:45,959 --> 03:55:47,639
thank you very much.

5016
03:55:47,639 --> 03:55:49,170
And here's how I think
it ought to be done.

5017
03:55:49,170 --> 03:55:51,540
Let's go try it and see who's right."

5018
03:55:51,540 --> 03:55:55,440
And that's proven I think
over and over in his case

5019
03:55:55,440 --> 03:55:56,870
to be a very powerful approach.

5020
03:55:56,870 --> 03:55:58,500
- If we just take that tangent,

5021
03:55:58,500 --> 03:56:02,969
there's a fascinating
interdisciplinary team at Neuralink

5022
03:56:02,969 --> 03:56:07,202
that you get to interact
with, including Elon.

5023
03:56:08,340 --> 03:56:11,792
What do you think is the
secret to a successful team?

5024
03:56:12,659 --> 03:56:13,559
What have you learned

5025
03:56:13,559 --> 03:56:15,609
from just getting to observe these folks?

5026
03:56:16,649 --> 03:56:19,472
World experts in different
disciplines work together.

5027
03:56:20,579 --> 03:56:25,000
- Yeah, there's a sweet
spot where people disagree

5028
03:56:27,299 --> 03:56:29,309
and forcefully speak their mind

5029
03:56:29,309 --> 03:56:31,412
and passionately defend their position,

5030
03:56:32,639 --> 03:56:36,750
and yet are still able to
accept information from others

5031
03:56:36,750 --> 03:56:40,020
and change their ideas when they're wrong.

5032
03:56:40,020 --> 03:56:42,180
And so I like the analogy

5033
03:56:42,180 --> 03:56:46,050
of sort of how you polish rocks.

5034
03:56:46,049 --> 03:56:50,579
You put hard things in a
hard container and spin it.

5035
03:56:50,579 --> 03:56:52,530
People bash against each other

5036
03:56:52,530 --> 03:56:57,120
and outcome's a more refined product.

5037
03:56:57,120 --> 03:57:01,560
And so to make a good team at Neuralink,

5038
03:57:01,559 --> 03:57:05,189
we've tried to find
people that are not afraid

5039
03:57:05,190 --> 03:57:07,260
to defend their ideas passionately.

5040
03:57:07,260 --> 03:57:12,260
And occasionally, strongly
disagree with people

5041
03:57:13,416 --> 03:57:15,840
that they're working with

5042
03:57:15,840 --> 03:57:18,632
and have the best idea come out on top.

5043
03:57:20,879 --> 03:57:23,099
It's not an easy balance, again,

5044
03:57:23,100 --> 03:57:26,370
to refer back to the primate brain.

5045
03:57:26,370 --> 03:57:28,380
It's not something that is inherently

5046
03:57:28,379 --> 03:57:30,842
built into the primate brain to say,

5047
03:57:32,197 --> 03:57:36,375
"I passionately put all
my chips on this position

5048
03:57:36,375 --> 03:57:37,950
and now I'm just gonna walk away from it.

5049
03:57:37,950 --> 03:57:39,840
Admit you were right."

5050
03:57:39,840 --> 03:57:43,889
Part of our brains tell us
that that is a power loss.

5051
03:57:43,889 --> 03:57:45,599
That is a loss of face,

5052
03:57:45,600 --> 03:57:47,844
a loss of standing in the community.

5053
03:57:47,843 --> 03:57:52,143
And now, you're a zeta chimp,

5054
03:57:53,010 --> 03:57:54,603
'cause your idea got trounced.

5055
03:57:56,159 --> 03:57:59,789
And you just have to recognize
that that little voice

5056
03:57:59,790 --> 03:58:01,410
in the back of your head is maladaptive

5057
03:58:01,409 --> 03:58:04,396
and it's not helping the team win.

5058
03:58:04,396 --> 03:58:05,460
- Yeah, you have to have the confidence

5059
03:58:05,459 --> 03:58:08,159
to be able to walk away from
an idea that you hold onto.

5060
03:58:08,159 --> 03:58:08,993
Yeah.
- Yeah.

5061
03:58:08,993 --> 03:58:11,040
- And if you do that often enough,

5062
03:58:11,040 --> 03:58:13,830
you're actually going to become

5063
03:58:13,829 --> 03:58:16,229
the best in the world at your thing.

5064
03:58:16,229 --> 03:58:18,750
I mean, that kind of that rapid iteration.

5065
03:58:18,750 --> 03:58:21,352
- Yeah, you'll at least be
a member of a winning team.

5066
03:58:22,440 --> 03:58:23,763
- Ride the wave.

5067
03:58:25,170 --> 03:58:26,069
What did you learn?

5068
03:58:26,069 --> 03:58:30,409
You mentioned there's a lot of
amazing neurosurgeons at USC.

5069
03:58:30,409 --> 03:58:33,360
What lessons about surgery and life

5070
03:58:33,360 --> 03:58:35,100
have you learned from those folks?

5071
03:58:35,100 --> 03:58:40,100
- Yeah, I think working
your ass off, working hard

5072
03:58:40,139 --> 03:58:44,519
while functioning as a member of a team,

5073
03:58:44,520 --> 03:58:47,613
getting a job done that
is incredibly difficult,

5074
03:58:49,530 --> 03:58:53,460
working incredibly long
hours, being up all night,

5075
03:58:53,459 --> 03:58:55,109
taking care of someone that

5076
03:58:55,110 --> 03:58:58,710
you think probably won't
survive no matter what you do.

5077
03:58:58,709 --> 03:59:03,000
Working hard to make people
that you passionately dislike

5078
03:59:03,000 --> 03:59:05,132
look good the next morning.

5079
03:59:06,659 --> 03:59:10,200
These folks were
relentless in their pursuit

5080
03:59:10,200 --> 03:59:15,200
of excellent neurosurgical
technique decade over decade.

5081
03:59:17,513 --> 03:59:21,300
And I think we're well-recognized
for that excellence.

5082
03:59:21,299 --> 03:59:25,319
Especially Marty Weiss,
Steve Giannotta, Mike Apuzzo,

5083
03:59:25,319 --> 03:59:30,029
they made huge contributions
not only to surgical technique,

5084
03:59:30,030 --> 03:59:33,190
but they built training
programs that trained

5085
03:59:34,200 --> 03:59:38,250
dozens or hundreds of
amazing neurosurgeons.

5086
03:59:38,250 --> 03:59:42,420
I was just lucky to kind
of be in their wake.

5087
03:59:42,420 --> 03:59:46,799
- What's that like, you
mentioned doing a surgery

5088
03:59:46,799 --> 03:59:51,119
where the person is likely not to survive.

5089
03:59:51,120 --> 03:59:52,443
Does that wear on you?

5090
03:59:54,180 --> 03:59:55,023
- Yeah.

5091
04:00:02,549 --> 04:00:05,582
It's especially challenging when you,

5092
04:00:10,590 --> 04:00:12,843
with all respect to our elders,

5093
04:00:13,709 --> 04:00:15,419
it doesn't hit so much

5094
04:00:15,420 --> 04:00:17,620
when you're taking care of an 80-year-old

5095
04:00:18,479 --> 04:00:23,479
and something was going to
get them pretty soon anyway.

5096
04:00:23,940 --> 04:00:27,060
And so you lose a patient like that,

5097
04:00:27,059 --> 04:00:29,549
and it was part of the natural course

5098
04:00:29,549 --> 04:00:33,932
of what is expected of them in
the coming years, regardless.

5099
04:00:36,450 --> 04:00:41,450
Taking care of a father of
two or three, four young kids,

5100
04:00:45,209 --> 04:00:49,529
someone in their 30s that
didn't have it coming,

5101
04:00:49,530 --> 04:00:52,320
and they show up in your ER

5102
04:00:52,319 --> 04:00:54,000
having their first seizure of their life,

5103
04:00:54,000 --> 04:00:57,090
and lo and behold, they've
got a huge, malignant,

5104
04:00:57,090 --> 04:01:00,153
inoperable or incurable brain tumor.

5105
04:01:01,079 --> 04:01:04,659
You can only do that, I
think, a handful of times

5106
04:01:06,239 --> 04:01:09,542
before it really starts
eating away at your armor.

5107
04:01:12,304 --> 04:01:14,639
Or a young mother that shows up

5108
04:01:14,639 --> 04:01:17,760
that has a giant hemorrhage in her brain

5109
04:01:17,760 --> 04:01:19,139
that she's not gonna survive from.

5110
04:01:19,139 --> 04:01:22,709
And they bring her four-year-old daughter

5111
04:01:22,709 --> 04:01:25,019
to say goodbye one last time

5112
04:01:25,020 --> 04:01:26,819
before they turn the ventilator off.

5113
04:01:30,600 --> 04:01:33,180
The great Henry Marsh is
a English neurosurgeon

5114
04:01:33,180 --> 04:01:34,013
who said it best.

5115
04:01:34,013 --> 04:01:35,790
I think he says that every neurosurgeon

5116
04:01:35,790 --> 04:01:37,560
carries with them a private graveyard,

5117
04:01:37,559 --> 04:01:39,092
and I definitely feel that,

5118
04:01:42,270 --> 04:01:43,983
especially with young parents.

5119
04:01:46,072 --> 04:01:46,905
That kills me.

5120
04:01:48,690 --> 04:01:50,313
They had a lot more to give.

5121
04:01:51,329 --> 04:01:53,879
The loss of those people specifically

5122
04:01:53,879 --> 04:01:58,879
has a knock on effect that's
going to make the world worse

5123
04:01:59,790 --> 04:02:03,330
for people for a long time.

5124
04:02:03,329 --> 04:02:07,143
And it's just hard to feel
powerless in the face of that.

5125
04:02:09,329 --> 04:02:14,329
And that's where I think you
have to be borderline evil

5126
04:02:15,479 --> 04:02:18,180
to fight against a company like Neuralink

5127
04:02:18,180 --> 04:02:21,870
or to constantly be taking pot shots at us

5128
04:02:21,870 --> 04:02:26,870
because what we're doing is
to try to fix that stuff.

5129
04:02:27,389 --> 04:02:29,222
We're trying to give people options,

5130
04:02:30,659 --> 04:02:32,612
to reduce suffering.

5131
04:02:34,881 --> 04:02:38,250
We're trying to take the pain out of life

5132
04:02:38,250 --> 04:02:43,250
that broken brains brings in.

5133
04:02:43,620 --> 04:02:48,450
And yeah, this is just our little way

5134
04:02:48,450 --> 04:02:51,333
that we're fighting back
against entropy, I guess.

5135
04:02:52,469 --> 04:02:55,349
- Yeah, the amount of
suffering that's endured

5136
04:02:55,350 --> 04:02:58,590
when some of the things
that we take for granted

5137
04:02:58,590 --> 04:03:02,579
that our brain is able to
do is taken away is immense.

5138
04:03:02,579 --> 04:03:03,780
And to be able to restore

5139
04:03:03,780 --> 04:03:06,390
some of that functionality is a real gift.

5140
04:03:06,389 --> 04:03:08,119
- Yeah, we're just starting.

5141
04:03:08,120 --> 04:03:09,993
We're gonna do so much more.

5142
04:03:11,879 --> 04:03:14,279
- Well, can you take me
through the full procedure

5143
04:03:14,280 --> 04:03:18,989
of implanting, say, the
N1 chip in Neuralink?

5144
04:03:18,989 --> 04:03:20,879
- Yeah, it's a really simple,

5145
04:03:20,879 --> 04:03:23,438
really simple, straightforward procedure.

5146
04:03:23,438 --> 04:03:28,438
The human part of the surgery
that I do is dead simple.

5147
04:03:29,909 --> 04:03:31,379
It's one of the most basic

5148
04:03:31,379 --> 04:03:34,529
neurosurgery procedures imaginable.

5149
04:03:34,530 --> 04:03:37,860
And I think there's evidence
that some version of it

5150
04:03:37,860 --> 04:03:40,800
has been done for thousands of years.

5151
04:03:40,799 --> 04:03:44,129
That there are examples I
think from ancient Egypt

5152
04:03:44,129 --> 04:03:48,876
of healed or partially healed
trephinations from Peru

5153
04:03:50,190 --> 04:03:53,520
or ancient times in South America

5154
04:03:53,520 --> 04:03:57,149
where these protosurgeons

5155
04:03:57,149 --> 04:03:59,909
would drill holes in people's skulls,

5156
04:03:59,909 --> 04:04:01,979
presumably to let out the evil spirits,

5157
04:04:01,979 --> 04:04:04,229
but maybe to drain blood clots.

5158
04:04:04,229 --> 04:04:06,779
And there's evidence of bone
healing around the edge,

5159
04:04:06,780 --> 04:04:08,310
meaning the people at least survive

5160
04:04:08,309 --> 04:04:11,636
some months after a procedure.

5161
04:04:11,637 --> 04:04:13,320
And so what we're doing is that.

5162
04:04:13,319 --> 04:04:16,559
We are making a cut in the
skin on the top of the head

5163
04:04:16,559 --> 04:04:20,439
over the area of the brain
that is the most potent

5164
04:04:21,329 --> 04:04:25,047
representation of hand intentions.

5165
04:04:25,047 --> 04:04:30,047
And so if you are an
expert concert pianist,

5166
04:04:31,049 --> 04:04:33,000
this part of your brain is lighting up

5167
04:04:33,000 --> 04:04:34,549
the entire time you're playing.

5168
04:04:35,459 --> 04:04:36,899
We call it the hand knob.

5169
04:04:36,899 --> 04:04:38,190
- The hand knob.
- Yeah.

5170
04:04:38,190 --> 04:04:40,173
- So it's all like the finger movement.

5171
04:04:41,520 --> 04:04:43,500
All of that is just firing away.

5172
04:04:43,500 --> 04:04:46,139
- Yep, there's a little squiggle
in the cortex right there.

5173
04:04:46,139 --> 04:04:47,369
One of the folds in the brain

5174
04:04:47,370 --> 04:04:50,520
is kind of doubly folded
right on that spot.

5175
04:04:50,520 --> 04:04:53,647
So you can look at it on an MRI and say,

5176
04:04:53,647 --> 04:04:55,320
"That's the hand knob."

5177
04:04:55,319 --> 04:04:57,209
And then you do a functional test

5178
04:04:57,209 --> 04:05:02,159
and a special kind of MRI called
an a functional MRI, fMRI.

5179
04:05:02,159 --> 04:05:04,500
And this part of the brain
lights up when people,

5180
04:05:04,500 --> 04:05:06,569
even quadriplegic people whose brains

5181
04:05:06,569 --> 04:05:08,610
aren't connected to their
finger movements anymore.

5182
04:05:08,610 --> 04:05:10,980
They imagine finger movements,

5183
04:05:10,979 --> 04:05:13,260
and this part of the
brain still lights up.

5184
04:05:13,260 --> 04:05:16,200
So we can ID that part of the brain

5185
04:05:16,200 --> 04:05:21,200
in anyone who's preparing
to enter our trial and say,

5186
04:05:21,426 --> 04:05:23,850
"Okay, that part of the brain, we confirm,

5187
04:05:23,850 --> 04:05:25,977
is your hand intention area."

5188
04:05:27,600 --> 04:05:30,899
And so I'll make a little cut in the skin,

5189
04:05:30,899 --> 04:05:33,180
we'll flap the skin open,

5190
04:05:33,180 --> 04:05:35,190
just like kind of opening
the hood of a car,

5191
04:05:35,190 --> 04:05:36,363
only a lot smaller.

5192
04:05:37,200 --> 04:05:42,200
Make a perfectly round one inch
diameter hole in the skull,

5193
04:05:43,440 --> 04:05:45,003
remove that bit of skull,

5194
04:05:46,590 --> 04:05:49,559
open the lining of the brain,
the covering of the brain.

5195
04:05:49,559 --> 04:05:53,222
It's like a little bag of
water that the brain floats in.

5196
04:05:54,090 --> 04:05:57,872
And then show that part
of the brain to our robot.

5197
04:05:59,250 --> 04:06:01,079
And then this is where the robot shines.

5198
04:06:01,079 --> 04:06:04,382
It can come in and take these tiny,

5199
04:06:05,579 --> 04:06:08,579
much smaller than human hair electrodes

5200
04:06:08,579 --> 04:06:12,270
and precisely insert them into the cortex,

5201
04:06:12,270 --> 04:06:16,710
into the surface of the brain
to a very precise depth,

5202
04:06:16,709 --> 04:06:19,799
in a very precise spot that
avoids all the blood vessels

5203
04:06:19,799 --> 04:06:22,379
that are coating the surface of the brain.

5204
04:06:22,379 --> 04:06:24,000
And after the robot's done with its part,

5205
04:06:24,000 --> 04:06:28,409
then the human comes back
in and puts the implant

5206
04:06:28,409 --> 04:06:32,159
into that hole in the
skull and covers it up,

5207
04:06:32,159 --> 04:06:33,479
screwing it down to the skull

5208
04:06:33,479 --> 04:06:35,972
and sewing the skin back together.

5209
04:06:37,547 --> 04:06:39,750
So the whole thing is a few hours long.

5210
04:06:39,750 --> 04:06:44,750
It's extremely low risk compared
to the average neurosurgery

5211
04:06:45,149 --> 04:06:47,489
involving the brain that might say,

5212
04:06:47,489 --> 04:06:49,139
open up a deep part of the brain

5213
04:06:49,139 --> 04:06:53,129
or manipulate blood vessels in the brain.

5214
04:06:53,129 --> 04:06:55,893
This opening on the surface of the brain,

5215
04:06:58,620 --> 04:07:01,290
with only cortical micro insertions,

5216
04:07:01,290 --> 04:07:04,980
carries significantly less risk

5217
04:07:04,979 --> 04:07:09,359
than a lot of the tumor
or aneurysm surgeries

5218
04:07:09,360 --> 04:07:10,739
that are routinely done.

5219
04:07:10,739 --> 04:07:13,559
- So cortical micro
insertions that are via robot

5220
04:07:13,559 --> 04:07:18,119
and computer vision are designed
to avoid the blood vessels.

5221
04:07:18,120 --> 04:07:18,990
- Exactly.

5222
04:07:18,989 --> 04:07:21,239
- So I know you're a bit biased here,

5223
04:07:21,239 --> 04:07:23,590
but let's compare human and machine.

5224
04:07:23,590 --> 04:07:26,250
- Sure.
- So what are human

5225
04:07:26,250 --> 04:07:29,040
surgeons able to do well,

5226
04:07:29,040 --> 04:07:32,440
and what are robot
surgeons able to do well

5227
04:07:33,840 --> 04:07:36,960
at this stage of our human
civilization development?

5228
04:07:36,959 --> 04:07:38,912
- Yeah, yeah, that's a good question.

5229
04:07:39,780 --> 04:07:44,520
Humans are general purpose machines.

5230
04:07:44,520 --> 04:07:48,270
We're able to adapt to unusual situations.

5231
04:07:48,270 --> 04:07:50,319
We're able to change the plan on the fly.

5232
04:07:53,250 --> 04:07:58,229
I remember well a surgery that
I was doing many years ago

5233
04:07:58,229 --> 04:08:03,229
down in San Diego, where the
plan was to open a small hole

5234
04:08:04,649 --> 04:08:08,670
behind the ear and go
reposition a blood vessel

5235
04:08:08,670 --> 04:08:11,309
that had come to lay on the facial nerve,

5236
04:08:11,309 --> 04:08:15,090
the trigeminal nerve, the
nerve that goes to the face.

5237
04:08:15,090 --> 04:08:17,340
When that blood vessel lays on the nerve,

5238
04:08:17,340 --> 04:08:21,750
it can cause just intolerable,
horrific shooting pain

5239
04:08:21,750 --> 04:08:25,110
that people describe like being
zapped with a cattle prod.

5240
04:08:25,110 --> 04:08:26,819
And so the beautiful, elegant surgery

5241
04:08:26,819 --> 04:08:30,899
is to go move this blood
vessel off the nerve.

5242
04:08:30,899 --> 04:08:33,629
The surgery team, we went in there

5243
04:08:33,629 --> 04:08:35,369
and started moving this blood vessel

5244
04:08:35,370 --> 04:08:37,530
and then found that there
was a giant aneurysm

5245
04:08:37,530 --> 04:08:40,140
on that blood vessel that
was not easily visible

5246
04:08:40,139 --> 04:08:41,879
on the pre-op scans.

5247
04:08:41,879 --> 04:08:44,396
And so the plan had to dynamically change,

5248
04:08:44,397 --> 04:08:48,330
and the human surgeons
had no problem with that.

5249
04:08:48,329 --> 04:08:50,610
We're trained for all those things.

5250
04:08:50,610 --> 04:08:53,610
Robots wouldn't do so
well in that situation,

5251
04:08:53,610 --> 04:08:55,773
at least in their current incarnation,

5252
04:08:56,670 --> 04:08:58,020
fully robotic surgery,

5253
04:08:58,020 --> 04:09:01,319
like the electrode insertion portion

5254
04:09:01,319 --> 04:09:04,289
of the Neuralink surgery.

5255
04:09:04,290 --> 04:09:06,360
It goes according to a set plan.

5256
04:09:06,360 --> 04:09:09,840
And so the humans can interrupt the flow

5257
04:09:09,840 --> 04:09:12,090
and change the plan, but the robot

5258
04:09:12,090 --> 04:09:14,250
can't really change the
plan midway through.

5259
04:09:14,250 --> 04:09:18,149
It operates according
to how it was programmed

5260
04:09:18,149 --> 04:09:19,500
and how it was asked to run.

5261
04:09:19,500 --> 04:09:23,250
It does its job very precisely,

5262
04:09:23,250 --> 04:09:26,309
but not with a wide degree of latitude

5263
04:09:26,309 --> 04:09:29,369
and how to react to changing conditions.

5264
04:09:29,370 --> 04:09:31,829
- So there could be just a
very large number of ways

5265
04:09:31,829 --> 04:09:33,539
that you could be surprised as a surgeon

5266
04:09:33,540 --> 04:09:36,420
when you enter a situation
that could be subtle things

5267
04:09:36,420 --> 04:09:38,520
that you have to dynamically adjust to.

5268
04:09:38,520 --> 04:09:40,120
- Correct.
- And robots are not

5269
04:09:41,280 --> 04:09:42,540
good at that.

5270
04:09:42,540 --> 04:09:44,160
- Currently.
- Currently.

5271
04:09:44,159 --> 04:09:49,159
I think we are at the
dawn of a new era with AI

5272
04:09:49,379 --> 04:09:54,269
of the parameters for robot responsiveness

5273
04:09:54,270 --> 04:09:56,783
to be dramatically broadened, right?

5274
04:09:56,782 --> 04:09:59,969
I mean, you can't look
at a self-driving car

5275
04:09:59,969 --> 04:10:03,813
and say that it's operating
under very narrow parameters.

5276
04:10:05,309 --> 04:10:07,350
If a chicken runs across the road,

5277
04:10:07,350 --> 04:10:10,050
it wasn't necessarily
programmed to deal with that,

5278
04:10:10,049 --> 04:10:14,340
specifically, but a Waymo
or a self-driving Tesla

5279
04:10:14,340 --> 04:10:17,760
would have no problem reacting
to that appropriately.

5280
04:10:17,760 --> 04:10:22,760
And so surgical robots aren't
there yet, but give it time.

5281
04:10:23,579 --> 04:10:24,989
- And then there could be a lot of,

5282
04:10:24,989 --> 04:10:27,420
sort of into like
semi-autonomous possibilities

5283
04:10:27,420 --> 04:10:32,340
of maybe a robotic surgeon could say,

5284
04:10:32,340 --> 04:10:34,799
this situation is perfectly familiar,

5285
04:10:34,799 --> 04:10:36,989
or the situation is not familiar.

5286
04:10:36,989 --> 04:10:39,899
And in the not familiar case,
a human could take over.

5287
04:10:39,899 --> 04:10:43,386
But basically like be very
conservative in saying,

5288
04:10:43,387 --> 04:10:46,620
"Okay, this for sure has
no issues, no surprises,

5289
04:10:46,620 --> 04:10:48,780
and let the humans deal
with the surprises,

5290
04:10:48,780 --> 04:10:50,329
with the edge cases, all that."

5291
04:10:51,479 --> 04:10:52,439
That's one possibility.

5292
04:10:52,440 --> 04:10:57,440
So you think eventually,
you'll be out of the job?

5293
04:10:58,920 --> 04:11:00,899
Well, you being neurosurgeon,

5294
04:11:00,899 --> 04:11:02,159
your job being neurosurgeon.

5295
04:11:02,159 --> 04:11:05,280
Humans, there will not
be many neurosurgeons

5296
04:11:05,280 --> 04:11:06,659
left on this earth.

5297
04:11:06,659 --> 04:11:09,239
- I'm not worried about my job

5298
04:11:09,239 --> 04:11:11,583
in the course of my professional life.

5299
04:11:12,659 --> 04:11:16,079
I think I would tell my
my kids not necessarily

5300
04:11:16,079 --> 04:11:17,799
to go in this line of work

5301
04:11:20,760 --> 04:11:24,239
depending on how things look in 20 years.

5302
04:11:24,239 --> 04:11:26,280
- It's so fascinating, 'cause I mean,

5303
04:11:26,280 --> 04:11:29,250
if I have a line of work, I
would say it's programming.

5304
04:11:29,250 --> 04:11:33,239
And if you ask me like for the
last, I don't know, 20 years,

5305
04:11:33,239 --> 04:11:34,920
what I would recommend for people,

5306
04:11:34,920 --> 04:11:36,513
I would tell 'em, yeah, go.

5307
04:11:37,350 --> 04:11:39,360
You will always have a job
if you're a programmer,

5308
04:11:39,360 --> 04:11:40,560
'cause there's more and more computers

5309
04:11:40,559 --> 04:11:43,412
and all this kind of
stuff and it pays well.

5310
04:11:44,700 --> 04:11:47,400
But then you realize these
large language models

5311
04:11:47,399 --> 04:11:50,399
come along and they're really
damn good at generating code.

5312
04:11:50,399 --> 04:11:52,596
So overnight, you could be surprised like,

5313
04:11:52,596 --> 04:11:55,469
"Wow, like what is the
contribution of the human really?"

5314
04:11:55,469 --> 04:11:56,646
But then you start to think,

5315
04:11:56,647 --> 04:12:00,630
"Okay, it does seem like
humans have ability,

5316
04:12:00,629 --> 04:12:03,269
like you said, to deal
with novel situations."

5317
04:12:03,270 --> 04:12:06,030
In the case of programming,
it's the ability

5318
04:12:06,030 --> 04:12:11,030
to kinda come up with novel
ideas to solve problems.

5319
04:12:12,479 --> 04:12:16,049
It seems like machines aren't
quite yet able to do that.

5320
04:12:16,049 --> 04:12:17,489
And when the stakes are very high,

5321
04:12:17,489 --> 04:12:20,610
when it's life critical,
as it is in surgery,

5322
04:12:20,610 --> 04:12:22,023
especially in neurosurgery,

5323
04:12:25,070 --> 04:12:26,370
the stakes are very high

5324
04:12:26,370 --> 04:12:28,290
for a robot to actually replace a human.

5325
04:12:28,290 --> 04:12:31,590
But it's fascinating that
in this case of Neuralink,

5326
04:12:31,590 --> 04:12:34,290
there's a human-robot collaboration.

5327
04:12:34,290 --> 04:12:36,070
- Yeah, yeah.

5328
04:12:36,069 --> 04:12:37,529
I do the parts it can't do,

5329
04:12:37,530 --> 04:12:39,180
and it does the parts I can't do.

5330
04:12:40,131 --> 04:12:41,673
And we are friends.

5331
04:12:41,674 --> 04:12:44,257
(Lex laughing)

5332
04:12:45,389 --> 04:12:49,319
- I saw that there's a
lot of practice going on.

5333
04:12:49,319 --> 04:12:51,231
So I mean, everything in Neuralink

5334
04:12:51,231 --> 04:12:54,149
is tested extremely rigorously.

5335
04:12:54,149 --> 04:12:56,699
But one of the things I
saw, that there's a proxy

5336
04:12:56,700 --> 04:12:58,770
on which the surgeries are performed.

5337
04:12:58,770 --> 04:12:59,819
- Yeah.
- So this is both

5338
04:12:59,819 --> 04:13:02,279
for the robot and for the human,

5339
04:13:02,280 --> 04:13:05,070
for everybody involved
in the entire pipeline.

5340
04:13:05,069 --> 04:13:07,409
What's that like practicing the surgery?

5341
04:13:07,409 --> 04:13:09,569
- It's pretty intense.

5342
04:13:09,569 --> 04:13:14,569
So there's no analog to
this in human surgery.

5343
04:13:14,940 --> 04:13:18,090
Human surgery is sort
of this artisanal craft

5344
04:13:18,090 --> 04:13:19,500
that's handed down directly

5345
04:13:19,500 --> 04:13:23,309
from master to pupil over the generations.

5346
04:13:23,309 --> 04:13:25,469
I mean, literally the way you learn

5347
04:13:25,469 --> 04:13:30,469
to be a surgeon on humans is
by doing surgery on humans.

5348
04:13:30,989 --> 04:13:33,190
I mean, first, you watch

5349
04:13:34,889 --> 04:13:38,069
your professors do a bunch of surgery,

5350
04:13:38,069 --> 04:13:40,350
and then finally, they
put the trivial parts

5351
04:13:40,350 --> 04:13:42,090
of the surgery into your hands,

5352
04:13:42,090 --> 04:13:43,770
and then the more complex parts.

5353
04:13:43,770 --> 04:13:46,436
And as your understanding of the point

5354
04:13:46,436 --> 04:13:49,229
and the purposes of the surgery increases,

5355
04:13:49,229 --> 04:13:52,199
you get more responsibility
in the perfect condition.

5356
04:13:52,200 --> 04:13:53,820
Doesn't always go well.

5357
04:13:53,819 --> 04:13:57,032
In Neuralink's case, the
approach is a bit different.

5358
04:13:58,950 --> 04:14:02,940
We, of course, practiced as
far as we could on animals.

5359
04:14:02,940 --> 04:14:04,893
We did hundreds of animal surgeries.

5360
04:14:06,659 --> 04:14:10,083
And when it came time
to do the first human,

5361
04:14:10,950 --> 04:14:14,920
we had just amazing
team of engineers build

5362
04:14:16,139 --> 04:14:18,420
incredibly lifelike models.

5363
04:14:18,420 --> 04:14:21,059
One of the engineers, Fran
Romano, in particular built

5364
04:14:21,059 --> 04:14:26,059
a pulsating brain in a
custom 3D printed skull

5365
04:14:26,430 --> 04:14:30,032
that matches exactly
the patient's anatomy,

5366
04:14:30,870 --> 04:14:35,490
including their face and
scalp characteristics.

5367
04:14:35,489 --> 04:14:38,932
And so when I was able to practice that,

5368
04:14:38,933 --> 04:14:42,940
I mean, it's as close as it
really reasonably should get

5369
04:14:45,510 --> 04:14:48,360
to being the real thing
and all the details,

5370
04:14:48,360 --> 04:14:52,409
including the having a mannequin body

5371
04:14:52,409 --> 04:14:54,809
attached to this custom head.

5372
04:14:54,809 --> 04:14:56,909
And so when we were doing
the practice surgeries,

5373
04:14:56,909 --> 04:15:01,079
we'd wheel that body into the CT scanner

5374
04:15:01,079 --> 04:15:04,739
and take a mock CT scan
and wheel it back in

5375
04:15:04,739 --> 04:15:08,856
and conduct all the normal
safety checks verbally.

5376
04:15:08,856 --> 04:15:12,209
"Stop, this patient, we're
confirming his identification,

5377
04:15:12,209 --> 04:15:15,599
is mannequin number blah, blah, blah."

5378
04:15:15,600 --> 04:15:18,750
And then opening the brain
in exactly the right spot

5379
04:15:18,750 --> 04:15:23,340
using standard operative
neuronavigation equipment,

5380
04:15:23,340 --> 04:15:26,190
standard surgical drills in the same OR

5381
04:15:26,190 --> 04:15:29,700
that we do all of our practice
surgeries in at Neuralink.

5382
04:15:29,700 --> 04:15:33,659
And having the skull open
and have the brain pulse,

5383
04:15:33,659 --> 04:15:35,969
which adds a degree of
difficulty for the robot

5384
04:15:35,969 --> 04:15:40,519
to perfectly precisely plan
and insert those electrodes

5385
04:15:40,520 --> 04:15:43,233
to the right depth and location.

5386
04:15:44,190 --> 04:15:49,170
And so yeah, we kind of broke new ground

5387
04:15:49,170 --> 04:15:52,590
on how extensively we
practiced for this surgery.

5388
04:15:52,590 --> 04:15:55,440
- So there was a historic moment,

5389
04:15:55,440 --> 04:15:57,040
a big milestone for Neuralink

5390
04:15:58,770 --> 04:16:03,270
in part for humanity with the first human

5391
04:16:03,270 --> 04:16:06,600
getting a Neuralink implant
in January of this year.

5392
04:16:06,600 --> 04:16:11,159
Take me through the surgery on Noland.

5393
04:16:11,159 --> 04:16:12,959
What did it feel like to be part of this?

5394
04:16:12,959 --> 04:16:14,129
- Yeah.

5395
04:16:14,129 --> 04:16:18,479
Well, we're lucky to have
just incredible partners

5396
04:16:18,479 --> 04:16:20,189
at the Barrow Neurologic Institute.

5397
04:16:20,190 --> 04:16:23,730
They are, I think, the premier

5398
04:16:23,729 --> 04:16:25,653
neurosurgical hospital in the world.

5399
04:16:29,399 --> 04:16:32,430
They made everything as easy as possible

5400
04:16:32,430 --> 04:16:37,139
for the trial to get going
and helped us immensely

5401
04:16:37,139 --> 04:16:41,819
with their expertise on
how to arrange the details.

5402
04:16:41,819 --> 04:16:46,199
It was a much more high
pressure surgery in some ways.

5403
04:16:46,200 --> 04:16:50,490
I mean, even though the
outcome wasn't particularly

5404
04:16:50,489 --> 04:16:53,913
in question in terms of
our participant safety,

5405
04:16:54,959 --> 04:16:59,189
the number of observers,
the number of people,

5406
04:16:59,190 --> 04:17:01,290
there's conference rooms full of people

5407
04:17:01,290 --> 04:17:03,453
watching live streams in the hospital,

5408
04:17:04,799 --> 04:17:06,659
rooting for this to go perfectly,

5409
04:17:06,659 --> 04:17:09,809
and that just adds pressure
that is not typical

5410
04:17:09,809 --> 04:17:14,809
for even the most intense
production neurosurgery.

5411
04:17:15,930 --> 04:17:18,600
Say, removing a tumor or placing

5412
04:17:18,600 --> 04:17:21,030
deep brain stimulation electrodes.

5413
04:17:21,030 --> 04:17:23,159
And it had never been
done on a human before.

5414
04:17:23,159 --> 04:17:25,112
There were unknown unknowns.

5415
04:17:27,329 --> 04:17:32,329
And so definitely, a
moderate pucker factor there

5416
04:17:33,899 --> 04:17:35,699
for the whole team,

5417
04:17:35,700 --> 04:17:38,909
not knowing if we were going to encounter,

5418
04:17:38,909 --> 04:17:43,909
say, a degree of brain
movement that was unanticipated

5419
04:17:44,790 --> 04:17:48,360
or a degree of brain
sag that took the brain

5420
04:17:48,360 --> 04:17:51,870
far away from the skull and
made it difficult to insert

5421
04:17:51,870 --> 04:17:54,690
or some other unknown unknown problem.

5422
04:17:54,690 --> 04:17:57,000
Fortunately, everything went well

5423
04:17:57,000 --> 04:18:01,200
and that surgery is one of the smoothest

5424
04:18:01,200 --> 04:18:03,150
outcomes we could have imagined.

5425
04:18:03,149 --> 04:18:04,049
- Were you nervous?

5426
04:18:04,049 --> 04:18:06,029
I mean, you're a bit quarterback

5427
04:18:06,030 --> 04:18:07,739
in the Super Bowl kind of situation.

5428
04:18:07,739 --> 04:18:09,719
- Extremely nervous.

5429
04:18:09,719 --> 04:18:10,979
Extremely.

5430
04:18:10,979 --> 04:18:12,656
I was very pleased when it went well

5431
04:18:12,656 --> 04:18:13,982
and when it was over.

5432
04:18:15,030 --> 04:18:17,550
Looking forward to number two.
- Yeah.

5433
04:18:17,549 --> 04:18:19,096
Even with all that practice, all of that,

5434
04:18:19,096 --> 04:18:21,659
you've never been in a situation

5435
04:18:21,659 --> 04:18:24,389
that's still high stakes in
terms of people watching.

5436
04:18:24,389 --> 04:18:26,459
And we should also probably mention,

5437
04:18:26,459 --> 04:18:28,772
given how the media
works, a lot of people,

5438
04:18:31,319 --> 04:18:35,209
maybe in a dark kind of way,
hoping it doesn't go well.

5439
04:18:35,209 --> 04:18:37,869
- Well, I think wealth is easy to hate

5440
04:18:39,299 --> 04:18:41,189
or envy or whatever.

5441
04:18:41,190 --> 04:18:46,190
And I think there's a whole
industry around driving clicks,

5442
04:18:48,510 --> 04:18:50,940
and bad news is great for clicks.

5443
04:18:50,940 --> 04:18:55,940
And so any way to take an
event and turn it into bad news

5444
04:18:57,030 --> 04:19:00,090
is gonna be really good for clicks.

5445
04:19:00,090 --> 04:19:03,450
- It just sucks because I think
it puts pressure on people.

5446
04:19:03,450 --> 04:19:07,140
It discourages people from trying to solve

5447
04:19:07,139 --> 04:19:09,299
really hard problems, because
to solve hard problems,

5448
04:19:09,299 --> 04:19:10,590
you have to go into the unknown.

5449
04:19:10,590 --> 04:19:13,170
You have to do things that
haven't been done before,

5450
04:19:13,170 --> 04:19:14,909
and you have to take risks.

5451
04:19:14,909 --> 04:19:16,649
- Yeah.
- Calculated risks.

5452
04:19:16,649 --> 04:19:18,420
You have to do all kinds
of safety precautions,

5453
04:19:18,420 --> 04:19:19,979
but risks nevertheless.

5454
04:19:19,979 --> 04:19:23,659
And I just wish there would
be more celebration of that,

5455
04:19:23,659 --> 04:19:27,194
of the risk taking versus
like people just waiting

5456
04:19:27,194 --> 04:19:30,840
on the sidelines, like
waiting for failure,

5457
04:19:30,840 --> 04:19:33,059
and then pointing out the failure.

5458
04:19:33,059 --> 04:19:33,899
Yeah, it sucks.

5459
04:19:33,899 --> 04:19:37,289
But in this case, it's
really great that everything

5460
04:19:37,290 --> 04:19:38,430
went just flawlessly,

5461
04:19:38,430 --> 04:19:41,520
but it's unnecessary
pressure, I would say.

5462
04:19:41,520 --> 04:19:46,050
- Now that there's a human
with literal skin in the game,

5463
04:19:46,049 --> 04:19:48,599
there's a participant whose wellbeing

5464
04:19:48,600 --> 04:19:49,770
rides on this doing well,

5465
04:19:49,770 --> 04:19:52,409
you have to be a pretty bad person

5466
04:19:52,409 --> 04:19:54,159
to be rooting for that to go wrong.

5467
04:19:55,290 --> 04:19:58,530
And so hopefully, people
look in the mirror

5468
04:19:58,530 --> 04:20:00,123
and realize that at some point.

