5979
04:45:12,240 --> 04:45:13,409
- Give it to like a teenager.

5980
04:45:13,409 --> 04:45:15,299
Like anytime I think
I'm good at something,

5981
04:45:15,299 --> 04:45:17,255
I'll always go to like, I don't know.

5982
04:45:17,255 --> 04:45:21,690
Even with the bit per second
of playing a video game,

5983
04:45:21,689 --> 04:45:23,009
you realize you give it to a teenager,

5984
04:45:23,009 --> 04:45:24,840
you've given your link to a teenager,

5985
04:45:24,840 --> 04:45:26,580
just the large number of them,

5986
04:45:26,580 --> 04:45:30,150
the kind of stuff, they get good at stuff.

5987
04:45:30,150 --> 04:45:34,953
They're gonna get like
hundreds of bits per second.

5988
04:45:35,798 --> 04:45:37,439
Even just with the current technology.

5989
04:45:37,439 --> 04:45:38,879
- Probably.

5990
04:45:38,880 --> 04:45:39,712
Probably.

5991
04:45:41,009 --> 04:45:42,459
- 'Cause it's also addicting,

5992
04:45:43,791 --> 04:45:46,520
the number go up aspect of it

5993
04:45:46,520 --> 04:45:48,147
of like improving and training,

5994
04:45:48,147 --> 04:45:50,490
'cause it is almost like a skill.

5995
04:45:50,490 --> 04:45:52,350
And plus, there's the
software on the other end

5996
04:45:52,349 --> 04:45:54,119
that adapts to you.

5997
04:45:54,119 --> 04:45:57,000
And especially if the
adapting procedure algorithm

5998
04:45:57,000 --> 04:45:58,110
becomes better and better and better,

5999
04:45:58,110 --> 04:45:59,520
you're like learning together.

6000
04:45:59,520 --> 04:46:01,650
- Yeah, we're scratching the
surface on that right now.

6001
04:46:01,650 --> 04:46:03,330
There's so much more to do.

6002
04:46:03,330 --> 04:46:06,090
- So on the complete other side of it,

6003
04:46:06,090 --> 04:46:10,200
you have an RFID chip implanted in you.

6004
04:46:10,200 --> 04:46:13,110
- Yeah.
- So I hear, nice.

6005
04:46:13,110 --> 04:46:14,100
- Little subtle thing.

6006
04:46:14,099 --> 04:46:16,539
- It's a passive device that you use

6007
04:46:17,400 --> 04:46:20,819
for unlocking like a
safe with top secrets,

6008
04:46:20,819 --> 04:46:22,259
or what do you use it for?

6009
04:46:22,259 --> 04:46:23,699
What's the story behind it?

6010
04:46:23,700 --> 04:46:25,610
- I'm not the first one.

6011
04:46:25,610 --> 04:46:28,229
There's this whole community
of weirdo biohackers

6012
04:46:28,229 --> 04:46:30,060
that have done this stuff,

6013
04:46:30,060 --> 04:46:32,920
and I think one of the
early use cases was storing

6014
04:46:33,930 --> 04:46:37,473
private crypto wallet keys and whatever.

6015
04:46:38,490 --> 04:46:42,273
I dabbled in that a bit
and had some fun with it.

6016
04:46:44,019 --> 04:46:46,170
- You have some bitcoin
implanted in your body somewhere.

6017
04:46:46,169 --> 04:46:47,189
You can't tell where, yeah.

6018
04:46:47,189 --> 04:46:49,158
- Yeah, actually, yeah.

6019
04:46:49,158 --> 04:46:50,069
(Lex laughing)

6020
04:46:50,069 --> 04:46:51,779
It was the modern day equivalent

6021
04:46:51,779 --> 04:46:53,860
of finding change in the sofa cushions

6022
04:46:54,720 --> 04:46:57,479
after I put some orphan crypto on there

6023
04:46:57,479 --> 04:46:58,529
that I thought was worthless

6024
04:46:58,529 --> 04:47:00,750
and forgot about it for a few years.

6025
04:47:00,750 --> 04:47:04,209
Went back and found that some
community of people loved it

6026
04:47:05,189 --> 04:47:06,959
and had propped up the value of it.

6027
04:47:06,959 --> 04:47:09,599
And so it had gone up 50 fold.

6028
04:47:09,599 --> 04:47:10,432
- Wow.
- So there was a lot

6029
04:47:10,433 --> 04:47:11,612
of change in those cushions.

6030
04:47:11,612 --> 04:47:13,620
(Lex laughing)

6031
04:47:13,619 --> 04:47:14,452
- That's hilarious.

6032
04:47:14,453 --> 04:47:17,262
- But the primary use case was mostly

6033
04:47:17,261 --> 04:47:20,129
as a tech demonstrator.

6034
04:47:20,130 --> 04:47:22,139
It has my business card on it.

6035
04:47:22,139 --> 04:47:26,790
You can scan that in by
touching it to your phone.

6036
04:47:26,790 --> 04:47:29,100
It opens the front door to my house,

6037
04:47:29,099 --> 04:47:30,046
whatever simple stuff.

6038
04:47:30,046 --> 04:47:31,259
- It's a cool step.

6039
04:47:31,259 --> 04:47:33,989
It's a cool leap to implant
something in your body.

6040
04:47:33,990 --> 04:47:37,980
I mean, perhaps, it's a
similar leap to a Neuralink

6041
04:47:37,979 --> 04:47:40,619
because for a lot of
people, that kind of notion

6042
04:47:40,619 --> 04:47:43,289
of putting something inside
your body, something electronic

6043
04:47:43,290 --> 04:47:45,510
inside a biological system is a big leap.

6044
04:47:45,509 --> 04:47:48,179
- Yeah, we have a kind
of a mysticism around

6045
04:47:48,180 --> 04:47:50,729
the barrier of our skin.

6046
04:47:50,729 --> 04:47:53,099
We're completely fine
with knee replacements,

6047
04:47:53,099 --> 04:47:57,422
hip replacements, dental implants.

6048
04:47:59,459 --> 04:48:04,459
But there's a mysticism still around

6049
04:48:04,950 --> 04:48:07,860
the inviable barrier that
the skull represents.

6050
04:48:07,860 --> 04:48:10,500
And I think that needs to be treated

6051
04:48:10,500 --> 04:48:13,950
like any other pragmatic barrier.

6052
04:48:13,950 --> 04:48:18,950
The question isn't, how incredible
is it to open the skull?

6053
04:48:19,110 --> 04:48:21,869
The question is, what
benefit can we provide?

6054
04:48:21,869 --> 04:48:23,489
- So from all the surgeries you done,

6055
04:48:23,490 --> 04:48:26,159
from everything you understand the brain,

6056
04:48:26,159 --> 04:48:28,860
how much does neuroplasticity
come into play?

6057
04:48:28,860 --> 04:48:30,959
How adaptable is the brain, for example,

6058
04:48:30,959 --> 04:48:33,750
just even in the case
of healing from surgery

6059
04:48:33,750 --> 04:48:36,569
or adapting to the post-surgery situation.

6060
04:48:36,569 --> 04:48:38,700
- The answer that is sad for me

6061
04:48:38,700 --> 04:48:42,840
and other people of my demographic is that

6062
04:48:42,840 --> 04:48:44,970
plasticity decreases with age.

6063
04:48:44,970 --> 04:48:47,220
Healing decreases with age.

6064
04:48:47,220 --> 04:48:52,220
I have too much gray hair
to be optimistic about that.

6065
04:48:52,740 --> 04:48:55,980
There are theoretical ways
to increase plasticity

6066
04:48:55,979 --> 04:48:58,739
using electrical stimulation.

6067
04:48:58,740 --> 04:49:02,280
Nothing that is totally proven out

6068
04:49:02,279 --> 04:49:06,029
as a robust enough mechanism
to offer widely to people.

6069
04:49:06,029 --> 04:49:10,709
But yeah, I think there's
cause for optimism

6070
04:49:10,709 --> 04:49:13,709
that we might find something
useful in terms of, say,

6071
04:49:13,709 --> 04:49:16,802
an implanted electrode
that improves learning.

6072
04:49:18,389 --> 04:49:21,270
Certainly, there's been
some really amazing work

6073
04:49:21,270 --> 04:49:25,500
recently from Nicholas
Schiff, Jonathan Baker,

6074
04:49:25,500 --> 04:49:29,040
and others who have a cohort of patients

6075
04:49:29,040 --> 04:49:31,049
with moderate traumatic brain injury

6076
04:49:31,049 --> 04:49:32,430
who have had electrodes placed

6077
04:49:32,430 --> 04:49:34,889
in the deep nucleus in the brain

6078
04:49:34,889 --> 04:49:36,329
called the centromedian nucleus

6079
04:49:36,330 --> 04:49:38,910
or just near central media nucleus.

6080
04:49:38,909 --> 04:49:42,119
And when they apply small
amounts of electricity

6081
04:49:42,119 --> 04:49:44,099
to that part of the brain,

6082
04:49:44,099 --> 04:49:46,379
it's almost like electronic caffeine.

6083
04:49:46,380 --> 04:49:50,790
They're able to improve
people's attention and focus.

6084
04:49:50,790 --> 04:49:54,659
They're able to improve how
well people can perform a task.

6085
04:49:54,659 --> 04:49:58,169
I think in one case, someone
who was unable to work

6086
04:49:58,169 --> 04:50:01,829
after the device was turned on,
they were able to get a job.

6087
04:50:01,830 --> 04:50:04,900
And that's sort of one of the holy grails

6088
04:50:05,970 --> 04:50:10,350
for me with Neuralink and
other technologies like this

6089
04:50:10,349 --> 04:50:13,562
is from a purely utilitarian standpoint,

6090
04:50:17,009 --> 04:50:19,500
can we make people able
to take care of themselves

6091
04:50:19,500 --> 04:50:21,630
and their families economically again?

6092
04:50:21,630 --> 04:50:24,569
Can we make it so someone
who's fully dependent

6093
04:50:24,569 --> 04:50:28,889
and even maybe requires a
lot of caregiver resources,

6094
04:50:28,889 --> 04:50:32,399
can we put them in a position
to be fully independent,

6095
04:50:32,400 --> 04:50:35,400
taking care of themselves,
giving back to their communities?

6096
04:50:36,389 --> 04:50:40,020
I think that's a very
compelling proposition,

6097
04:50:40,020 --> 04:50:41,850
and what motivates a lot of what I do

6098
04:50:41,849 --> 04:50:44,969
and what a lot of the people
at Neuralink are working for.

6099
04:50:44,970 --> 04:50:46,470
- It's just a cool possibility

6100
04:50:46,470 --> 04:50:49,712
that if you put a Neuralink in
there, that the brain adapts,

6101
04:50:49,712 --> 04:50:52,709
like the other part of
the brain adapts too.

6102
04:50:52,709 --> 04:50:54,299
- Yeah.
- And integrates it.

6103
04:50:54,299 --> 04:50:56,819
The capacity of the brain to
do that is really interesting.

6104
04:50:56,819 --> 04:51:00,840
Probably unknown to the degree
to which you can do that,

6105
04:51:00,840 --> 04:51:05,159
but you're now connecting
an external thing to it,

6106
04:51:05,159 --> 04:51:09,093
especially once it's doing stimulation,

6107
04:51:10,139 --> 04:51:15,139
like the biological brain
and the electronic brain

6108
04:51:16,619 --> 04:51:18,512
outside of it working together.

6109
04:51:18,512 --> 04:51:20,913
Like the possibilities there
are really interesting.

6110
04:51:20,913 --> 04:51:23,343
It's still unknown but interesting.

6111
04:51:24,509 --> 04:51:26,189
It feels like the brain is really good

6112
04:51:26,189 --> 04:51:28,169
at adapting to whatever.

6113
04:51:28,169 --> 04:51:29,309
- Yeah.
- But of course,

6114
04:51:29,310 --> 04:51:31,863
it is a system that by itself is already,

6115
04:51:34,200 --> 04:51:36,450
like everything serves a purpose

6116
04:51:36,450 --> 04:51:39,540
and so you don't wanna
mess with it too much.

6117
04:51:39,540 --> 04:51:43,409
- Yeah, it's like, eliminating a species

6118
04:51:43,409 --> 04:51:45,060
from an ecology.

6119
04:51:45,060 --> 04:51:47,340
You don't know what the
delicate interconnections

6120
04:51:47,340 --> 04:51:48,512
and dependencies are.

6121
04:51:49,979 --> 04:51:54,599
The brain is certainly a
delicate, complex beast.

6122
04:51:54,599 --> 04:51:59,599
And we don't know every
potential downstream consequence

6123
04:52:00,689 --> 04:52:04,259
of a single change that we make.

6124
04:52:04,259 --> 04:52:08,189
- Do you see yourself
doing, so you mentioned P1,

6125
04:52:08,189 --> 04:52:11,309
surgeries of P2, P3, P4, P5?

6126
04:52:11,310 --> 04:52:14,159
Just more and more and more humans.

6127
04:52:14,159 --> 04:52:17,639
- I think it's a certain
kind of brittleness

6128
04:52:17,639 --> 04:52:20,099
or a failure on the company's side

6129
04:52:20,099 --> 04:52:23,492
if we need me to do all the surgeries.

6130
04:52:25,409 --> 04:52:27,930
I think something that I would very much

6131
04:52:27,930 --> 04:52:32,760
like to work towards is a
process that is so simple

6132
04:52:32,759 --> 04:52:34,559
and so robust on the surgery side

6133
04:52:34,560 --> 04:52:36,723
that literally anyone could do it.

6134
04:52:38,159 --> 04:52:42,659
We wanna get away from
requiring intense expertise

6135
04:52:42,659 --> 04:52:47,099
or intense experience to
have this successfully done

6136
04:52:47,099 --> 04:52:51,779
and make it as simple and
translatable as possible.

6137
04:52:51,779 --> 04:52:54,299
I mean, I would love it if
every neurosurgeon on the planet

6138
04:52:54,299 --> 04:52:55,862
had no problem doing this.

6139
04:52:58,110 --> 04:53:00,600
I think we're probably far
from a regulatory environment

6140
04:53:00,599 --> 04:53:04,109
that would allow people
that aren't neurosurgeons

6141
04:53:04,110 --> 04:53:06,903
to do this, but not impossible.

6142
04:53:08,099 --> 04:53:10,500
- All right, I'll sign up for that.

6143
04:53:10,500 --> 04:53:13,233
Did you ever anthropomorphize
the robot R1?

6144
04:53:14,610 --> 04:53:17,340
Like do you give it a name?

6145
04:53:17,340 --> 04:53:18,630
Do you see it as like a friend,

6146
04:53:18,630 --> 04:53:19,633
as like working together with you?

6147
04:53:19,633 --> 04:53:21,659
- I mean, to a certain degree it's-

6148
04:53:21,659 --> 04:53:23,509
- Or anatomy who's gonna get the gap.

6149
04:53:25,742 --> 04:53:29,672
- To a certain degree, yeah,
it's complex relationship.

6150
04:53:31,200 --> 04:53:32,909
- All the good relationships are.

6151
04:53:32,909 --> 04:53:35,130
- It's funny when, in the
middle of the surgery,

6152
04:53:35,130 --> 04:53:37,200
there's a part of it where I stand

6153
04:53:37,200 --> 04:53:40,049
basically shoulder to
shoulder with the robot.

6154
04:53:40,049 --> 04:53:44,939
And so if you're in the room
reading the body language,

6155
04:53:44,939 --> 04:53:46,799
that's my brother in arms there.

6156
04:53:46,799 --> 04:53:49,952
We're working together
on the same problem.

6157
04:53:52,020 --> 04:53:53,733
Yeah, I'm not threatened by it.

6158
04:53:55,349 --> 04:53:58,680
- Keep telling yourself that. (laughs)

6159
04:53:58,680 --> 04:54:01,712
How have all the surgeries that
you've done over the years,

6160
04:54:03,556 --> 04:54:05,760
the people you've helped and the stakes,

6161
04:54:05,759 --> 04:54:07,409
the high stakes that you've mentioned,

6162
04:54:07,409 --> 04:54:10,863
how has that changed your
understanding of life and death?

6163
04:54:13,619 --> 04:54:14,452
- Yeah.

6164
04:54:19,470 --> 04:54:22,290
It gives you a very visceral sense,

6165
04:54:22,290 --> 04:54:23,490
and this makes sound trite,

6166
04:54:23,490 --> 04:54:25,170
but it gives you a very visceral sense

6167
04:54:25,169 --> 04:54:26,972
that death is inevitable.

6168
04:54:28,290 --> 04:54:33,290
On one hand, you are, as a neurosurgeon,

6169
04:54:33,299 --> 04:54:34,829
you're deeply involved in these

6170
04:54:34,830 --> 04:54:38,223
like just hard to fathom tragedies:

6171
04:54:40,470 --> 04:54:45,470
young parents dying, leaving
a four-year-old behind say.

6172
04:54:49,560 --> 04:54:51,273
And on the other hand,

6173
04:54:52,500 --> 04:54:54,700
it takes the sting out of it a bit because

6174
04:54:56,220 --> 04:55:00,870
you see how just mind
numbingly universal death is.

6175
04:55:00,869 --> 04:55:05,073
There's zero chance that
I'm going to avoid it.

6176
04:55:06,360 --> 04:55:10,770
I know techno optimists right now

6177
04:55:10,770 --> 04:55:12,750
and longevity buffs right now

6178
04:55:12,750 --> 04:55:17,750
would disagree on that 0.0% estimate.

6179
04:55:18,119 --> 04:55:21,479
But I don't see any chance

6180
04:55:21,479 --> 04:55:24,329
that our generation is going to avoid it.

6181
04:55:24,330 --> 04:55:25,740
Entropy is a powerful force,

6182
04:55:25,740 --> 04:55:30,740
and we are very ornate,
delicate, brittle DNA machines

6183
04:55:30,933 --> 04:55:33,690
that aren't up to the
cosmic ray bombardment

6184
04:55:33,689 --> 04:55:34,983
that we're subjected to.

6185
04:55:35,939 --> 04:55:37,772
So on the one hand,

6186
04:55:38,669 --> 04:55:43,112
every human that has ever
lived died or will die.

6187
04:55:44,639 --> 04:55:49,020
On the other hand, it's just
one of the hardest things

6188
04:55:49,020 --> 04:55:53,430
to imagine inflicting on anyone

6189
04:55:53,430 --> 04:55:55,860
that you love is having them gone.

6190
04:55:55,860 --> 04:55:58,860
I'm sure you've had friends
that aren't living anymore

6191
04:55:58,860 --> 04:56:01,293
and it's hard to even think about them.

6192
04:56:03,209 --> 04:56:08,209
And so I wish I had arrived
at the point of nirvana

6193
04:56:12,360 --> 04:56:14,790
where death doesn't have a sting.

6194
04:56:14,790 --> 04:56:17,673
I'm not worried about it,
but I can at least say

6195
04:56:17,672 --> 04:56:19,972
that I'm comfortable
with the certainty of it.

6196
04:56:21,209 --> 04:56:26,209
If not, having found out how
to take the tragedy out of it

6197
04:56:27,180 --> 04:56:31,349
when I think about my
kids either not having me

6198
04:56:31,349 --> 04:56:34,323
or me not having them or my wife.

6199
04:56:35,610 --> 04:56:36,720
- Maybe I have come to accepting

6200
04:56:36,720 --> 04:56:39,933
intellectual certainty of
it, but it may be the pain

6201
04:56:43,049 --> 04:56:45,360
that comes with losing
the people you love,

6202
04:56:45,360 --> 04:56:46,680
I don't think I've come to understand

6203
04:56:46,680 --> 04:56:51,389
the existential aspect of it.

6204
04:56:51,389 --> 04:56:54,264
Like that this is gonna end.

6205
04:56:54,264 --> 04:56:59,264
And I don't mean like in some trite way.

6206
04:56:59,909 --> 04:57:04,909
I mean like, it certainly feels
like it's not going to end.

6207
04:57:05,759 --> 04:57:08,159
Like you live life like
it's not going to end.

6208
04:57:08,159 --> 04:57:09,389
- [Matthew] Right.

6209
04:57:09,389 --> 04:57:10,889
- And the fact that this light

6210
04:57:10,889 --> 04:57:13,259
that's shining this consciousness

6211
04:57:13,259 --> 04:57:18,259
is going to no longer be,
in one moment, maybe today,

6212
04:57:20,340 --> 04:57:23,009
it fills me when I really am able

6213
04:57:23,009 --> 04:57:27,209
to load all that in with
Ernest Becker's terror.

6214
04:57:27,209 --> 04:57:28,529
Like it's a real fear.

6215
04:57:28,529 --> 04:57:30,539
I think people aren't always honest

6216
04:57:30,540 --> 04:57:32,583
with how terrifying it is.

6217
04:57:33,900 --> 04:57:35,220
I think the more you are able

6218
04:57:35,220 --> 04:57:38,220
to really think through it,
the more terrifying it is.

6219
04:57:38,220 --> 04:57:39,063
It's not such a simple thing.

6220
04:57:39,062 --> 04:57:41,312
Oh well, it's the way life is.

6221
04:57:42,180 --> 04:57:47,180
If you really can load that in, it's hard.

6222
04:57:47,520 --> 04:57:49,229
But I think that's why the stoics did it,

6223
04:57:49,229 --> 04:57:52,380
because it like helps you
get your shit together

6224
04:57:52,380 --> 04:57:55,319
and be like, well, the moment,

6225
04:57:55,319 --> 04:57:58,676
every single moment you're
alive is just beautiful.

6226
04:57:58,676 --> 04:58:01,233
And it's terrifying that it's gonna end,

6227
04:58:04,362 --> 04:58:07,590
like almost like you're
shivering in the cold

6228
04:58:07,590 --> 04:58:10,409
a child helpless, this kind of feeling.

6229
04:58:10,409 --> 04:58:13,290
And then it makes you,
when you have warmth,

6230
04:58:13,290 --> 04:58:14,370
when you have the safety,

6231
04:58:14,369 --> 04:58:16,983
when you have the love
to really appreciate it.

6232
04:58:18,509 --> 04:58:21,272
I feel like sometimes, in your position,

6233
04:58:22,290 --> 04:58:25,683
when you mentioned
armor, just to see death,

6234
04:58:26,790 --> 04:58:30,450
it might make you not be able to see that,

6235
04:58:30,450 --> 04:58:32,369
the finiteness of life,

6236
04:58:32,369 --> 04:58:36,779
because if you kept looking
at that, it might break you.

6237
04:58:36,779 --> 04:58:40,229
So it's good to know that you're kind of

6238
04:58:40,229 --> 04:58:42,336
still struggling with that,

6239
04:58:42,336 --> 04:58:45,779
that there's the neurosurgeon
and then there's a human.

6240
04:58:45,779 --> 04:58:48,506
And the human is still
able to struggle with that

6241
04:58:48,507 --> 04:58:51,569
and feel the fear of that
and the pain of that.

6242
04:58:51,569 --> 04:58:54,659
- Yeah, it definitely
makes you ask the question

6243
04:58:54,659 --> 04:58:59,250
of how long, how many
of these can you see?

6244
04:58:59,250 --> 04:59:02,516
And not say, "I can't do this anymore."

6245
04:59:07,049 --> 04:59:08,849
But I mean, you said it well.

6246
04:59:08,849 --> 04:59:12,959
I think it gives you an
opportunity to just appreciate

6247
04:59:12,959 --> 04:59:14,253
that you're alive today.

6248
04:59:16,020 --> 04:59:20,760
And I've got three kids
and an amazing wife

6249
04:59:20,759 --> 04:59:23,939
and I'm really happy.

6250
04:59:23,939 --> 04:59:24,930
Things are good.

6251
04:59:24,930 --> 04:59:27,209
I get to help on a project
that I think matters.

6252
04:59:27,209 --> 04:59:28,979
I think it moves us forward.

6253
04:59:28,979 --> 04:59:30,810
I'm a very lucky person.

6254
04:59:30,810 --> 04:59:33,340
- It's the early steps of a potentially

6255
04:59:35,159 --> 04:59:37,590
gigantic leap for humanity.

6256
04:59:37,590 --> 04:59:39,119
It's a really interesting one.

6257
04:59:39,119 --> 04:59:40,619
And it's cool 'cause like you,

6258
04:59:40,619 --> 04:59:42,329
you read about all this stuff in history

6259
04:59:42,330 --> 04:59:43,860
where it's like the early days.

6260
04:59:43,860 --> 04:59:46,229
I've been reading, before
going to the Amazon,

6261
04:59:46,229 --> 04:59:49,979
I would read about explorers
that would go and explore

6262
04:59:49,979 --> 04:59:52,950
even the Amazon jungle for the first time.

6263
04:59:52,950 --> 04:59:54,930
Those are the early steps.

6264
04:59:54,930 --> 04:59:56,639
Or early steps into space,

6265
04:59:56,639 --> 04:59:58,259
early steps in any discipline,

6266
04:59:58,259 --> 05:00:00,032
in physics and mathematics.

6267
05:00:01,229 --> 05:00:04,380
And it's cool 'cause this
is like, on the grand scale,

6268
05:00:04,380 --> 05:00:05,940
these are the early steps

6269
05:00:05,939 --> 05:00:09,479
into delving deep into the human brain.

6270
05:00:09,479 --> 05:00:11,009
So not just observing the brain,

6271
05:00:11,009 --> 05:00:13,769
but be able to interact
with the human brain.

6272
05:00:13,770 --> 05:00:14,939
It's gonna help a lot of people,

6273
05:00:14,939 --> 05:00:19,229
but it also might help us understand

6274
05:00:19,229 --> 05:00:20,759
what the hell's going on in there.

6275
05:00:20,759 --> 05:00:24,599
- Yeah, I think ultimately,
we wanna give people

6276
05:00:24,599 --> 05:00:26,612
more levers that they can pull, right?

6277
05:00:26,613 --> 05:00:28,923
Like you wanna give people options.

6278
05:00:29,759 --> 05:00:33,219
If you can give someone
a dial that they can turn

6279
05:00:34,290 --> 05:00:35,852
on how happy they are,

6280
05:00:37,709 --> 05:00:40,110
I think that makes people
really uncomfortable.

6281
05:00:40,110 --> 05:00:45,110
But now, talk about major
depressive disorder.

6282
05:00:45,599 --> 05:00:47,699
Talk about people that
are committing suicide

6283
05:00:47,700 --> 05:00:49,653
at an alarming rate in this country.

6284
05:00:50,490 --> 05:00:55,490
And try to justify that queasiness

6285
05:00:57,805 --> 05:01:02,159
in that light of you
can give people a knob

6286
05:01:02,159 --> 05:01:06,289
to take away suicidal
ideation, suicidal intention.

6287
05:01:06,289 --> 05:01:08,760
I would give them that knob.

6288
05:01:08,759 --> 05:01:11,411
I don't know how you
justify not doing that.

6289
05:01:11,412 --> 05:01:12,599
- Yeah, you can think about like

6290
05:01:12,599 --> 05:01:14,159
all the suffering that's
going on in the world.

6291
05:01:14,159 --> 05:01:15,389
Like every single human being

6292
05:01:15,389 --> 05:01:17,545
that's suffering right now,

6293
05:01:17,545 --> 05:01:18,719
it'll be a glowing red dot.

6294
05:01:18,720 --> 05:01:20,400
The more suffering, the more it's glowing.

6295
05:01:20,400 --> 05:01:22,800
And you just see the
map of human suffering,

6296
05:01:22,799 --> 05:01:26,009
and any technology that
allows you to dim that light

6297
05:01:26,009 --> 05:01:30,750
of suffering on a grand
scale is pretty exciting,

6298
05:01:30,750 --> 05:01:31,856
because there's a lot of people suffering

6299
05:01:31,856 --> 05:01:33,692
and most of them suffer quietly.

6300
05:01:37,380 --> 05:01:39,513
We look away too often,

6301
05:01:40,979 --> 05:01:44,159
and we should remember
those that are suffering,

6302
05:01:44,159 --> 05:01:46,770
'cause once again, most of
them are suffering quietly.

6303
05:01:46,770 --> 05:01:50,400
- Well, and on a grander
scale, the fabric of society,

6304
05:01:50,400 --> 05:01:52,890
people have a lot of complaints about

6305
05:01:52,889 --> 05:01:56,369
how our social fabric is working

6306
05:01:56,369 --> 05:01:59,319
or not working, how our politics
is working or not working.

6307
05:02:01,650 --> 05:02:05,940
Those things are made
of neurochemistry too,

6308
05:02:05,939 --> 05:02:07,079
in aggregate, right?

6309
05:02:07,080 --> 05:02:10,320
Like our politics is
composed of individuals

6310
05:02:10,319 --> 05:02:15,319
with human brains and, the
way it works or doesn't work

6311
05:02:15,930 --> 05:02:20,930
is potentially tunable in
the sense that, I don't know,

6312
05:02:20,970 --> 05:02:24,300
say remove our addictive behaviors

6313
05:02:24,299 --> 05:02:27,090
or tune our addictive
behaviors for social media

6314
05:02:27,090 --> 05:02:31,439
or our addiction to outrage,
our addiction to sharing

6315
05:02:31,439 --> 05:02:35,402
the most angry political
tweet we can find.

6316
05:02:37,979 --> 05:02:41,069
I don't think that leads
to a functional society.

6317
05:02:41,069 --> 05:02:45,016
And if you had options

6318
05:02:46,259 --> 05:02:51,122
for people to moderate
that maladaptive behavior,

6319
05:02:52,049 --> 05:02:54,270
there could be huge benefits to society.

6320
05:02:54,270 --> 05:02:56,369
Maybe we could all work together

6321
05:02:56,369 --> 05:03:00,029
a little more harmoniously
toward useful ends.

6322
05:03:00,029 --> 05:03:02,009
- There's a sweet spot,
like you mentioned,

6323
05:03:02,009 --> 05:03:04,500
you don't wanna completely
remove all the dark sides

6324
05:03:04,500 --> 05:03:08,819
of human nature 'cause those
kind of are somehow necessary

6325
05:03:08,819 --> 05:03:09,930
to make the whole thing work.

6326
05:03:09,930 --> 05:03:11,040
But there's a sweet spot.

6327
05:03:11,040 --> 05:03:12,240
- Yeah, I agree.

6328
05:03:12,240 --> 05:03:14,520
We gotta suffer a little,

6329
05:03:14,520 --> 05:03:16,500
just not so much that you lose hope.

6330
05:03:16,500 --> 05:03:17,430
- Yeah.

6331
05:03:17,430 --> 05:03:19,049
We knew all the surgeries you've done.

6332
05:03:19,049 --> 05:03:21,029
Have you seen consciousness in there ever?

6333
05:03:21,029 --> 05:03:22,579
Was there like a glowing light?

6334
05:03:23,654 --> 05:03:27,270
- I have this sense that I never found it.

6335
05:03:27,270 --> 05:03:31,233
Never removed it, like a
dementor in Harry Potter.

6336
05:03:32,729 --> 05:03:36,389
I have this sense that
consciousness is a lot less magical

6337
05:03:36,389 --> 05:03:39,363
than our instincts wanna claim it is.

6338
05:03:41,279 --> 05:03:45,719
It seems to me like a useful
analog for thinking about

6339
05:03:45,720 --> 05:03:48,573
what consciousness is in the brain,

6340
05:03:50,880 --> 05:03:55,440
is that we have a really
good intuitive understanding

6341
05:03:55,439 --> 05:03:59,009
of what it means to, say, touch your skin

6342
05:03:59,009 --> 05:04:00,509
and know what's being touched.

6343
05:04:02,490 --> 05:04:04,980
I think consciousness is just that level

6344
05:04:04,979 --> 05:04:06,389
of sensory mapping applied

6345
05:04:06,389 --> 05:04:10,139
to the thought processes
in the brain itself.

6346
05:04:10,139 --> 05:04:12,509
So what I'm saying is consciousness

6347
05:04:12,509 --> 05:04:17,509
is the sensation of some part
of your brain being active.

6348
05:04:17,729 --> 05:04:20,369
So you feel it working.

6349
05:04:20,369 --> 05:04:21,809
You feel the part of your brain

6350
05:04:21,810 --> 05:04:25,840
that thinks of red things
or winged creatures

6351
05:04:27,090 --> 05:04:29,790
or the taste of coffee.

6352
05:04:29,790 --> 05:04:33,389
You feel those parts of
your brain being active

6353
05:04:33,389 --> 05:04:36,809
the way that I'm feeling my
palm being touched, right?

6354
05:04:36,810 --> 05:04:41,810
And that sensory system
that feels the brain working

6355
05:04:42,540 --> 05:04:43,397
is consciousness.

6356
05:04:43,397 --> 05:04:45,299
- That's so brilliant.

6357
05:04:45,299 --> 05:04:48,149
It's the same way, it's
the sensation of touch

6358
05:04:48,150 --> 05:04:50,400
when you're touching a thing.

6359
05:04:50,400 --> 05:04:52,980
Consciousness is the sensation of you

6360
05:04:52,979 --> 05:04:56,909
feeling your brain working,
your brain thinking,

6361
05:04:56,909 --> 05:04:59,155
your brain perceiving.

6362
05:04:59,155 --> 05:05:03,239
- Which isn't like a
warping of space and time

6363
05:05:03,240 --> 05:05:06,060
or some quantum field effect, right?

6364
05:05:06,060 --> 05:05:07,110
It's nothing magical.

6365
05:05:07,110 --> 05:05:10,360
People always wanna
ascribe to consciousness

6366
05:05:11,400 --> 05:05:13,743
something truly different.

6367
05:05:14,580 --> 05:05:16,680
And there's this awesome long history

6368
05:05:16,680 --> 05:05:18,900
of people looking at whatever the latest

6369
05:05:18,900 --> 05:05:21,813
discovery in physics is
to explain consciousness,

6370
05:05:22,709 --> 05:05:24,119
because it's the most magical,

6371
05:05:24,119 --> 05:05:27,266
the most out there thing
that you can think of.

6372
05:05:27,266 --> 05:05:30,659
And people always wanna do
that with consciousness.

6373
05:05:30,659 --> 05:05:31,860
I don't think that's necessary.

6374
05:05:31,860 --> 05:05:34,950
It's just a very useful

6375
05:05:34,950 --> 05:05:38,280
and gratifying way of
feeling your brain work.

6376
05:05:38,279 --> 05:05:40,590
- And as we said, it's
one heck of a brain.

6377
05:05:40,590 --> 05:05:41,880
- [Matthew] Yeah.

6378
05:05:41,880 --> 05:05:43,979
- Everything we see around
us, everything we love,

6379
05:05:43,979 --> 05:05:44,939
everything that's beautiful,

6380
05:05:44,939 --> 05:05:48,659
it came from brains like these.

6381
05:05:48,659 --> 05:05:52,349
- It's all electrical activity
happening inside your skull.

6382
05:05:52,349 --> 05:05:56,789
- And I, for one, am grateful
that there's people like you

6383
05:05:56,790 --> 05:06:01,290
that are exploring all
the ways that it works

6384
05:06:01,290 --> 05:06:03,240
and all the ways it can be made better.

6385
05:06:04,111 --> 05:06:04,943
- Thanks, Lex.

6386
05:06:04,943 --> 05:06:06,360
- Thank you so much for talking today.

6387
05:06:06,360 --> 05:06:08,069
- It's been a joy.

6388
05:06:08,069 --> 05:06:09,869
Thanks for listening to this conversation

6389
05:06:09,869 --> 05:06:12,000
with Matthew MacDougall.

6390
05:06:12,000 --> 05:06:16,139
And now, dear friends,
here's Bliss Chapman,

6391
05:06:16,139 --> 05:06:20,069
Brain Interface Software
lead at Neuralink.

6392
05:06:20,069 --> 05:06:22,770
You told me that you've
met hundreds of people

6393
05:06:22,770 --> 05:06:25,619
with spinal cord injuries or with ALS

6394
05:06:25,619 --> 05:06:28,529
and that your motivation
for helping at Neuralink

6395
05:06:28,529 --> 05:06:30,629
is grounded in wanting to help them.

6396
05:06:30,630 --> 05:06:32,069
Can you describe this motivation?

6397
05:06:32,069 --> 05:06:32,902
- Yeah.

6398
05:06:32,902 --> 05:06:34,769
First, just a thank you to all the people

6399
05:06:34,770 --> 05:06:36,389
I've gotten a chance to speak with,

6400
05:06:36,389 --> 05:06:38,399
for sharing their stories with me.

6401
05:06:38,400 --> 05:06:41,700
I don't think there's any
world really in which I can

6402
05:06:41,700 --> 05:06:44,400
share their stories as
powerful way as they can.

6403
05:06:44,400 --> 05:06:47,310
But just I think to summarize
at a very high level

6404
05:06:47,310 --> 05:06:52,260
what I hear over and over
again is that people with ALS

6405
05:06:52,259 --> 05:06:54,299
or severe spinal cord injury in a place

6406
05:06:54,299 --> 05:06:57,090
where they basically can't
move physically anymore,

6407
05:06:57,090 --> 05:06:59,729
really at the end of the day
are looking for independence.

6408
05:06:59,729 --> 05:07:02,279
And that can mean different
things for different people.

6409
05:07:02,279 --> 05:07:04,709
For some folks, it can mean
the ability just to be able

6410
05:07:04,709 --> 05:07:06,869
to communicate again
independently without needing

6411
05:07:06,869 --> 05:07:09,629
to wear something on their face,
without needing a caretaker

6412
05:07:09,630 --> 05:07:11,880
to be able to put
something in their mouth.

6413
05:07:11,880 --> 05:07:13,950
For some folks, it can mean
independence to be able

6414
05:07:13,950 --> 05:07:17,639
to work again, to be able to
navigate a computer digitally,

6415
05:07:17,639 --> 05:07:19,259
efficiently enough to
be able to get a job,

6416
05:07:19,259 --> 05:07:21,959
to be able to support themself,
to be able to move out

6417
05:07:21,959 --> 05:07:23,340
and ultimately be able to support themself

6418
05:07:23,340 --> 05:07:25,529
after their family maybe
isn't there anymore

6419
05:07:25,529 --> 05:07:27,329
to take care of them.

6420
05:07:27,330 --> 05:07:29,670
And for some folks, it's as simple as

6421
05:07:29,669 --> 05:07:31,500
just being able to respond
to their kid in time

6422
05:07:31,500 --> 05:07:35,639
before they run away or get
interested in something else.

6423
05:07:35,639 --> 05:07:39,419
And these are deeply personal

6424
05:07:39,419 --> 05:07:42,419
and sort of very human problems.

6425
05:07:42,419 --> 05:07:44,399
And what strikes me again and again

6426
05:07:44,400 --> 05:07:46,050
when talking with these folks is that

6427
05:07:46,049 --> 05:07:48,509
this is actually an engineering problem.

6428
05:07:48,509 --> 05:07:50,939
This is a problem that
with the right resources,

6429
05:07:50,939 --> 05:07:54,270
with the right team, we can
make a lot of progress on.

6430
05:07:54,270 --> 05:07:56,467
And at the end of the day,

6431
05:07:56,467 --> 05:07:58,139
I think that's a deeply inspiring message

6432
05:07:58,139 --> 05:08:01,139
and something that makes me
excited to get up every day.

6433
05:08:01,139 --> 05:08:03,090
- So it's both an engineering problem

6434
05:08:03,090 --> 05:08:05,130
in terms of a BCI, for example,

6435
05:08:05,130 --> 05:08:06,930
that can give them capabilities

6436
05:08:06,930 --> 05:08:08,520
where they can interact with the world.

6437
05:08:08,520 --> 05:08:11,430
But also on the other side,
it's an engineering problem

6438
05:08:11,430 --> 05:08:13,529
for the rest of the world
to make it more accessible

6439
05:08:13,529 --> 05:08:15,930
for people living with quadriplegia.

6440
05:08:15,930 --> 05:08:18,270
- Yeah, and actually,
I'll take a broad view

6441
05:08:18,270 --> 05:08:19,560
sort of lens on this for a second.

6442
05:08:19,560 --> 05:08:22,409
I think I'm very in favor of anyone

6443
05:08:22,409 --> 05:08:23,610
working in this problem space.

6444
05:08:23,610 --> 05:08:26,430
So beyond BCI, I'm happy and excited

6445
05:08:26,430 --> 05:08:28,020
and willing to support any way I can

6446
05:08:28,020 --> 05:08:29,520
folks working on eye tracking systems,

6447
05:08:29,520 --> 05:08:31,680
working on speech to text systems,

6448
05:08:31,680 --> 05:08:34,979
working on head trackers or
mouse sticks or quad sticks.

6449
05:08:34,979 --> 05:08:36,149
And I've met many engineers

6450
05:08:36,150 --> 05:08:38,940
and folks in the community
that do exactly those things.

6451
05:08:38,939 --> 05:08:41,699
And I think for the people
we're trying to help,

6452
05:08:41,700 --> 05:08:43,860
it doesn't matter what the
complexity of the solution is

6453
05:08:43,860 --> 05:08:45,930
as long as the problem is solved.

6454
05:08:45,930 --> 05:08:47,580
And I wanna emphasize

6455
05:08:47,580 --> 05:08:49,590
that there can be many solutions out there

6456
05:08:49,590 --> 05:08:51,360
that can help with these problems.

6457
05:08:51,360 --> 05:08:54,930
And BCI is one of a
collection of such solutions.

6458
05:08:54,930 --> 05:08:56,099
So BCI, in particular,

6459
05:08:56,099 --> 05:08:58,199
I think offers several advantages here.

6460
05:08:58,200 --> 05:09:00,569
And I think the folks that
recognize this immediately

6461
05:09:00,569 --> 05:09:02,279
are usually the people who
have spinal cord injury

6462
05:09:02,279 --> 05:09:03,750
or some form of paralysis.

6463
05:09:03,750 --> 05:09:04,919
Usually, you don't have to explain to them

6464
05:09:04,919 --> 05:09:06,539
why this might be something
that could be helpful.

6465
05:09:06,540 --> 05:09:07,680
It's usually pretty self-evident.

6466
05:09:07,680 --> 05:09:10,080
But for the rest of us
folks that don't live

6467
05:09:10,080 --> 05:09:11,130
with severe spinal cord injury

6468
05:09:11,130 --> 05:09:14,069
or who don't know somebody with ALS,

6469
05:09:14,069 --> 05:09:16,229
it's not often obvious why
you would want a brain implant

6470
05:09:16,229 --> 05:09:18,720
to be able to connect
and navigate a computer.

6471
05:09:18,720 --> 05:09:19,552
And it's surprisingly nuanced,

6472
05:09:19,552 --> 05:09:22,380
and to the degree that
I've learned a huge amount

