7211
05:36:59,549 --> 05:37:01,319
is how accurate are those assumptions.

7212
05:37:01,319 --> 05:37:03,096
For example, you might say,

7213
05:37:03,097 --> 05:37:04,590
"Hey, user, push upwards

7214
05:37:04,590 --> 05:37:06,990
and follow the speed of this cursor,"

7215
05:37:06,990 --> 05:37:09,210
and your heuristic might be
that they're trying to do it

7216
05:37:09,209 --> 05:37:10,770
exactly what that cursor's trying to do.

7217
05:37:10,770 --> 05:37:12,389
Another competing heuristic might be

7218
05:37:12,389 --> 05:37:13,860
they're actually trying
to go slightly faster

7219
05:37:13,860 --> 05:37:14,700
at the beginning of the movement

7220
05:37:14,700 --> 05:37:16,380
and slightly slower at the end.

7221
05:37:16,380 --> 05:37:18,510
And those competing heuristics
may or may not be accurate

7222
05:37:18,509 --> 05:37:20,639
reflections of what the
user's trying to do.

7223
05:37:20,639 --> 05:37:21,967
Another version of the task might be,

7224
05:37:21,967 --> 05:37:25,560
"Hey, user, imagine moving
this cursor a fixed offset.

7225
05:37:25,560 --> 05:37:27,030
So rather than follow the cursor,

7226
05:37:27,029 --> 05:37:29,579
just try to move it exactly
200 pixels to the right."

7227
05:37:29,580 --> 05:37:31,500
So here's the cursor, here's the target.

7228
05:37:31,500 --> 05:37:32,610
Okay, cursor disappears.

7229
05:37:32,610 --> 05:37:34,590
Try to move that now invisible cursor

7230
05:37:34,590 --> 05:37:36,180
200 pixels to the right.

7231
05:37:36,180 --> 05:37:37,830
And the assumption in that
case would be that the user

7232
05:37:37,830 --> 05:37:41,220
can actually modulate
correctly that position offset,

7233
05:37:41,220 --> 05:37:42,690
but that position offset assumption

7234
05:37:42,689 --> 05:37:45,419
might be a weaker
assumption, and therefore,

7235
05:37:45,419 --> 05:37:47,159
potentially you can make it more accurate

7236
05:37:47,159 --> 05:37:48,750
than these heuristics that
are trying to guesstimate

7237
05:37:48,750 --> 05:37:50,970
at each millisecond what
the user's trying to do.

7238
05:37:50,970 --> 05:37:52,680
So you can imagine different tasks

7239
05:37:52,680 --> 05:37:55,260
that make different
assumptions about the nature

7240
05:37:55,259 --> 05:37:58,169
of the user intention and
those assumptions being correct

7241
05:37:58,169 --> 05:37:59,943
is what I would think of as a clean label.

7242
05:37:59,943 --> 05:38:02,790
- For that step, what are we
supposed to be visualizing?

7243
05:38:02,790 --> 05:38:05,340
There's a cursor and you
wanna move that cursor

7244
05:38:05,340 --> 05:38:06,840
to the right or the left or up and down

7245
05:38:06,840 --> 05:38:09,422
or maybe move them by a certain offset.

7246
05:38:10,500 --> 05:38:13,229
So that's one way, is that the
best way to do calibration?

7247
05:38:13,229 --> 05:38:15,479
So for example, an alternative crazy way

7248
05:38:15,479 --> 05:38:17,253
that probably is playing a role here

7249
05:38:17,253 --> 05:38:19,740
is a game like Webgrid,

7250
05:38:19,740 --> 05:38:23,880
where you're just getting a
very large amount of data,

7251
05:38:23,880 --> 05:38:25,920
the person playing a game,

7252
05:38:25,919 --> 05:38:28,589
where if they're in a state of flow,

7253
05:38:28,590 --> 05:38:33,590
maybe you can get clean
signal as a side effect.

7254
05:38:33,659 --> 05:38:34,492
- [Bliss] Yep.

7255
05:38:36,002 --> 05:38:38,520
- Is that not an effective
way for initial calibration?

7256
05:38:38,520 --> 05:38:39,352
- Yeah, great question.

7257
05:38:39,352 --> 05:38:40,409
There's a lot to unpack there.

7258
05:38:40,409 --> 05:38:43,709
So the first thing I
would draw a distinction

7259
05:38:43,709 --> 05:38:46,139
between a sort of open
loop, first closed loop.

7260
05:38:46,139 --> 05:38:47,399
So open loop, what I mean by that

7261
05:38:47,400 --> 05:38:49,740
is the user is sort of
going from zero to one.

7262
05:38:49,740 --> 05:38:51,120
They have no model at all,

7263
05:38:51,119 --> 05:38:52,319
and they're trying to get to the place

7264
05:38:52,319 --> 05:38:55,020
where they have some
level of control at all.

7265
05:38:55,020 --> 05:38:58,020
In that setup, you really
need to have some task

7266
05:38:58,020 --> 05:38:59,790
that gives the user a hint
of what you want them to do

7267
05:38:59,790 --> 05:39:01,170
such that you can build this mapping again

7268
05:39:01,169 --> 05:39:03,959
from brain data to output.

7269
05:39:03,959 --> 05:39:06,329
Then once they have a model,
you could imagine them

7270
05:39:06,330 --> 05:39:08,880
using that model and
actually adapting to it

7271
05:39:08,880 --> 05:39:10,979
and figuring out the right
way to use it themself

7272
05:39:10,979 --> 05:39:12,329
and then retraining on that data

7273
05:39:12,330 --> 05:39:14,640
to give you sort of a
boost in performance.

7274
05:39:14,639 --> 05:39:15,959
There's a lot of challenges associated

7275
05:39:15,959 --> 05:39:17,909
with both of these techniques
and we can sort of rabbit hole

7276
05:39:17,909 --> 05:39:19,154
into both of 'em, if you're interested.

7277
05:39:19,154 --> 05:39:21,869
But the sort of challenge
with the open loop task

7278
05:39:21,869 --> 05:39:24,180
is that the user themself doesn't get

7279
05:39:24,180 --> 05:39:26,580
proprioceptive feedback
about what they're doing.

7280
05:39:26,580 --> 05:39:29,460
They don't necessarily perceive themself

7281
05:39:29,459 --> 05:39:31,739
or feel the mouse under their hand

7282
05:39:31,740 --> 05:39:33,090
when they're using an open,

7283
05:39:33,090 --> 05:39:34,619
when they're trying to do
an open loop calibration.

7284
05:39:34,619 --> 05:39:36,059
They're being asked to perform something.

7285
05:39:36,060 --> 05:39:39,420
Like imagine if you sort of
had your whole right arm numbed

7286
05:39:39,419 --> 05:39:40,992
and you stuck it in a box
and you couldn't see it.

7287
05:39:40,992 --> 05:39:42,899
So you had no visual feedback

7288
05:39:42,900 --> 05:39:44,400
and you had no proprioceptive feedback

7289
05:39:44,400 --> 05:39:47,040
about what the position or
activity of your arm was.

7290
05:39:47,040 --> 05:39:48,900
And now you're asked, okay,
given this thing on the screen

7291
05:39:48,900 --> 05:39:51,990
that's moving from left to
right, match that speed.

7292
05:39:51,990 --> 05:39:55,740
And you basically can
try your best to invoke

7293
05:39:55,740 --> 05:39:57,930
whatever that imagined
action is in your brain

7294
05:39:57,930 --> 05:39:59,819
that's moving the cursor
from left to right.

7295
05:39:59,819 --> 05:40:02,489
But in any situation,
you're gonna be inaccurate

7296
05:40:02,490 --> 05:40:04,677
and maybe inconsistent
in how you do that task.

7297
05:40:04,676 --> 05:40:05,939
And so that's sort of the fundamental

7298
05:40:05,939 --> 05:40:07,319
challenge of open loop.

7299
05:40:07,319 --> 05:40:09,270
The challenge with closed loop is that,

7300
05:40:09,270 --> 05:40:11,282
once the user's given a model,

7301
05:40:12,450 --> 05:40:15,510
and they're able to start
moving the mouse on their own,

7302
05:40:15,509 --> 05:40:18,329
they're going to very
naturally adapt to that model.

7303
05:40:18,330 --> 05:40:20,730
And that co-adaptation
between the model learning,

7304
05:40:20,729 --> 05:40:22,470
what they're doing, and the user learning

7305
05:40:22,470 --> 05:40:24,870
how to use the model may
not find you the best

7306
05:40:24,869 --> 05:40:25,770
sort of global minima.

7307
05:40:25,770 --> 05:40:28,920
And maybe that your first
model was noisy in some ways

7308
05:40:28,919 --> 05:40:31,851
or maybe just had some like quirk,

7309
05:40:31,851 --> 05:40:33,479
like if there's some like
part of the data distribution

7310
05:40:33,479 --> 05:40:36,509
that didn't cover super well,
and the user now figures out

7311
05:40:36,509 --> 05:40:38,519
because they're a
brilliant user like Noland.

7312
05:40:38,520 --> 05:40:41,310
They figured out the right
sequence of imagined motions

7313
05:40:41,310 --> 05:40:42,720
or the right angle they
have to hold their hand at

7314
05:40:42,720 --> 05:40:43,898
to get it to work.

7315
05:40:43,898 --> 05:40:45,060
And they'll get it to work great,

7316
05:40:45,060 --> 05:40:46,979
but then the next day, they
come back to their device

7317
05:40:46,979 --> 05:40:48,149
and maybe they don't remember exactly

7318
05:40:48,150 --> 05:40:49,307
all the tricks that they
used the previous day.

7319
05:40:49,307 --> 05:40:51,930
And so there's a complicated
sort of feedback cycle here

7320
05:40:51,930 --> 05:40:54,052
that can emerge and can make it

7321
05:40:54,052 --> 05:40:56,549
a very, very difficult debugging process.

7322
05:40:56,549 --> 05:41:00,000
- Okay, there's a lot of really
fascinating things there.

7323
05:41:00,000 --> 05:41:03,422
Yeah, actually, just to
stay on the closed loop,

7324
05:41:07,259 --> 05:41:09,779
I've seen situations,
this actually happened

7325
05:41:09,779 --> 05:41:12,869
watching psychology grad students.

7326
05:41:12,869 --> 05:41:14,489
They use piece of software
when they don't know

7327
05:41:14,490 --> 05:41:15,420
how to program themselves.

7328
05:41:15,419 --> 05:41:17,549
They use piece of software
that somebody else wrote,

7329
05:41:17,549 --> 05:41:18,899
and it has a bunch of bugs.

7330
05:41:19,830 --> 05:41:21,060
And they figure out like,

7331
05:41:21,060 --> 05:41:22,830
and they've been using it for years.

7332
05:41:22,830 --> 05:41:24,627
They figured out ways to work around it.

7333
05:41:24,627 --> 05:41:25,860
Oh, that just happens.

7334
05:41:25,860 --> 05:41:29,430
Like nobody like considers
maybe we should fix this.

7335
05:41:29,430 --> 05:41:30,630
They just adapt.

7336
05:41:30,630 --> 05:41:33,090
And that's a really interesting notion,

7337
05:41:33,090 --> 05:41:37,770
that we were really good at
adapting, but you need to still,

7338
05:41:37,770 --> 05:41:39,779
that might not be the optimal.

7339
05:41:39,779 --> 05:41:41,279
Okay, so how do you solve that problem?

7340
05:41:41,279 --> 05:41:43,349
Do you have to restart from scratch

7341
05:41:43,349 --> 05:41:44,879
every once in a while kind of thing?

7342
05:41:44,880 --> 05:41:46,409
- Yeah, it's a good question.

7343
05:41:46,409 --> 05:41:47,340
First and foremost, I would say

7344
05:41:47,340 --> 05:41:48,599
this is not a solved problem.

7345
05:41:48,599 --> 05:41:51,539
And for anyone who's listening in academia

7346
05:41:51,540 --> 05:41:54,150
who works on BCIs, I would
also say this is not a problem

7347
05:41:54,150 --> 05:41:57,060
that's solved by simply
scaling channel account.

7348
05:41:57,060 --> 05:41:58,229
Maybe that can help and you can get

7349
05:41:58,229 --> 05:41:59,579
sort of richer covariance structures

7350
05:41:59,580 --> 05:42:00,990
that you can use to exploit

7351
05:42:00,990 --> 05:42:02,760
when trying to come up with
good labeling strategies.

7352
05:42:02,759 --> 05:42:04,649
But if you're interested in problems,

7353
05:42:04,650 --> 05:42:05,909
that aren't gonna be solved inherently

7354
05:42:05,909 --> 05:42:08,189
by scaling channel account,
this is one of them.

7355
05:42:08,189 --> 05:42:09,629
Yeah, so how do you solve it?

7356
05:42:09,630 --> 05:42:10,650
It's not a solved problem.

7357
05:42:10,650 --> 05:42:12,840
That's the first thing I
wanna make sure gets across.

7358
05:42:12,840 --> 05:42:15,790
The second thing is, any solution
that involves closed loop

7359
05:42:16,830 --> 05:42:18,810
is going to become a very
difficult debugging problem.

7360
05:42:18,810 --> 05:42:21,900
And one of my sort of general
heuristics for choosing

7361
05:42:21,900 --> 05:42:23,610
what prompts to tackle is
that you wanna choose the one

7362
05:42:23,610 --> 05:42:25,470
that's gonna be the easiest to debug,

7363
05:42:25,470 --> 05:42:27,479
'cause if you can do that,

7364
05:42:27,479 --> 05:42:30,689
even if the ceiling is
lower, you're gonna be able

7365
05:42:30,689 --> 05:42:32,579
to move faster because you have a tighter

7366
05:42:32,580 --> 05:42:34,457
iteration loop debugging the problem.

7367
05:42:34,456 --> 05:42:35,609
And in the open loop setting,

7368
05:42:35,610 --> 05:42:37,560
there's not a feedback cycle debug

7369
05:42:37,560 --> 05:42:38,426
with the user in the loop.

7370
05:42:38,426 --> 05:42:39,840
And so there's some reason to think

7371
05:42:39,840 --> 05:42:43,409
that that should be an
easier debugging problem.

7372
05:42:43,409 --> 05:42:44,970
The other thing that's worth understanding

7373
05:42:44,970 --> 05:42:46,680
is that even in a closed loop setting,

7374
05:42:46,680 --> 05:42:48,900
there's no special software
magic of how to infer

7375
05:42:48,900 --> 05:42:50,909
what the user is truly attempting to do.

7376
05:42:50,909 --> 05:42:52,560
In the closed loop setting,
although they're moving

7377
05:42:52,560 --> 05:42:54,960
the cursor on the screen, they
may be attempting something

7378
05:42:54,959 --> 05:42:56,790
different than what your
model is outputting.

7379
05:42:56,790 --> 05:42:58,650
So what the model is
outputting is not a signal

7380
05:42:58,650 --> 05:43:00,330
that you can use to retrain
if you want to be able

7381
05:43:00,330 --> 05:43:01,590
to improve the model further.

7382
05:43:01,590 --> 05:43:04,409
You still have this very
complicated guesstimation

7383
05:43:04,409 --> 05:43:06,689
or unsupervised problem of figuring out

7384
05:43:06,689 --> 05:43:09,689
what is the true user intention
underlying that signal.

7385
05:43:09,689 --> 05:43:11,759
And so the open loop problem
has the nice property

7386
05:43:11,759 --> 05:43:13,709
of being easy to debug.

7387
05:43:13,709 --> 05:43:15,419
And the second nice property of,

7388
05:43:15,419 --> 05:43:17,369
it has all the same
information and content

7389
05:43:17,369 --> 05:43:18,770
as the closed loop scenario.

7390
05:43:19,830 --> 05:43:21,203
Another thing I wanna mention and call out

7391
05:43:21,203 --> 05:43:23,340
is that this problem
doesn't need to be solved

7392
05:43:23,340 --> 05:43:26,159
in order to give useful control to people.

7393
05:43:26,159 --> 05:43:28,439
Even today with the solutions we have now

7394
05:43:28,439 --> 05:43:30,689
and that academia has
built up over decades,

7395
05:43:30,689 --> 05:43:32,609
the level of control that can be given

7396
05:43:32,610 --> 05:43:35,580
to a user today is quite useful.

7397
05:43:35,580 --> 05:43:36,737
It doesn't need to be solved

7398
05:43:36,737 --> 05:43:38,310
to get to that level of control.

7399
05:43:38,310 --> 05:43:40,170
But again, I wanna build
the world's best mouse.

7400
05:43:40,169 --> 05:43:42,059
I wanna make it so good

7401
05:43:42,060 --> 05:43:44,159
that it's not even a
question that you want it.

7402
05:43:44,159 --> 05:43:48,240
And to build the world's best
mouse, the superhuman version,

7403
05:43:48,240 --> 05:43:51,177
you really need to nail that problem.

7404
05:43:51,176 --> 05:43:54,270
And a couple maybe details
of previous studies

7405
05:43:54,270 --> 05:43:56,220
that we've done internally that
I think are very interesting

7406
05:43:56,220 --> 05:43:58,470
to understand when thinking
about how to solve this problem,

7407
05:43:58,470 --> 05:44:00,953
the first is that even when
you have ground truth data

7408
05:44:00,953 --> 05:44:02,397
of what the user's trying to do,

7409
05:44:02,397 --> 05:44:04,380
and you can get this with
an able-bodied monkey,

7410
05:44:04,380 --> 05:44:06,600
a monkey that has a
Neuralink device implanted

7411
05:44:06,599 --> 05:44:08,430
and moving a mouse to control a computer,

7412
05:44:08,430 --> 05:44:11,069
even with that ground truth dataset,

7413
05:44:11,069 --> 05:44:13,829
it turns out that the
optimal thing to predict

7414
05:44:13,830 --> 05:44:16,230
to produce high performance BCI

7415
05:44:16,229 --> 05:44:18,689
is not just the direct
control of the mouse.

7416
05:44:18,689 --> 05:44:20,189
You can imagine building dataset

7417
05:44:20,189 --> 05:44:21,266
of what's going on in the brain

7418
05:44:21,266 --> 05:44:24,090
and what is the mouse
exactly doing on the table.

7419
05:44:24,090 --> 05:44:25,680
And it turns out that
if you build the mapping

7420
05:44:25,680 --> 05:44:27,330
from neuro spikes to predict exactly

7421
05:44:27,330 --> 05:44:29,700
what the mouse is doing,
that model will perform

7422
05:44:29,700 --> 05:44:32,220
worse than a model that
is trained to predict

7423
05:44:32,220 --> 05:44:33,360
sort of higher level assumptions

7424
05:44:33,360 --> 05:44:35,130
about what the user might be trying to do.

7425
05:44:35,130 --> 05:44:36,840
For example, assuming
that the monkey is trying

7426
05:44:36,840 --> 05:44:38,459
to go in a straight line to the target,

7427
05:44:38,459 --> 05:44:40,379
it turns out that making those assumptions

7428
05:44:40,380 --> 05:44:42,299
is actually more effective

7429
05:44:42,299 --> 05:44:44,250
in producing a model
than actually predicting

7430
05:44:44,250 --> 05:44:45,082
the underlying hand movement.

7431
05:44:45,082 --> 05:44:46,169
- So the intention,

7432
05:44:46,169 --> 05:44:48,119
not like the physical
movement or whatever.

7433
05:44:48,119 --> 05:44:49,739
- Yeah.
- There's obviously

7434
05:44:49,740 --> 05:44:51,330
a really strong correlation
between the two,

7435
05:44:51,330 --> 05:44:54,570
but the intention is a more
powerful thing to be chasing.

7436
05:44:54,569 --> 05:44:55,739
- [Bliss] Right.

7437
05:44:55,740 --> 05:44:57,630
- Well, that's also super interesting.

7438
05:44:57,630 --> 05:45:01,680
I mean, the intention
itself is fascinating,

7439
05:45:01,680 --> 05:45:03,479
because yes, with the BCI here,

7440
05:45:03,479 --> 05:45:06,060
in this case, with a digital telepathy,

7441
05:45:06,060 --> 05:45:08,909
you're acting on the
intention, not the action,

7442
05:45:08,909 --> 05:45:10,709
which is why there's an experience

7443
05:45:10,709 --> 05:45:13,259
of like feeling like it's happening

7444
05:45:13,259 --> 05:45:15,509
before you meant for it to happen.

7445
05:45:15,509 --> 05:45:17,159
That is so cool.

7446
05:45:17,159 --> 05:45:18,540
And that is why you could achieve

7447
05:45:18,540 --> 05:45:20,520
like superhuman performance problem

7448
05:45:20,520 --> 05:45:22,400
in terms of the control of the mouse.

7449
05:45:22,400 --> 05:45:24,540
So for open loop, just to clarify,

7450
05:45:24,540 --> 05:45:27,870
so whenever the person is tasked

7451
05:45:27,869 --> 05:45:29,789
to like move the mouse to the right,

7452
05:45:29,790 --> 05:45:31,139
you said there's not feedback

7453
05:45:31,139 --> 05:45:35,279
so they don't get to get that satisfaction

7454
05:45:35,279 --> 05:45:38,819
of like actually getting
it to move, right?

7455
05:45:38,819 --> 05:45:41,520
- You could imagine giving
the user feedback on a screen,

7456
05:45:41,520 --> 05:45:43,260
but it's difficult, because at this point,

7457
05:45:43,259 --> 05:45:44,939
you don't know what
they're attempting to do.

