we can represent well.

7945
06:03:23,819 --> 06:03:25,169
But it's really up to
him to go and explore

7946
06:03:25,169 --> 06:03:27,089
and figure out what works the best.

7947
06:03:27,090 --> 06:03:30,479
- But at which point does
he no longer visualize

7948
06:03:30,479 --> 06:03:32,549
the movement of his body
and is just visualizing

7949
06:03:32,549 --> 06:03:33,809
the movement of the cursor?

7950
06:03:33,810 --> 06:03:35,807
- Yeah.
- How quickly does he go from,

7951
06:03:35,807 --> 06:03:37,280
how quickly does he get there?

7952
06:03:37,279 --> 06:03:38,909
- So this happened on a Tuesday.

7953
06:03:38,909 --> 06:03:40,409
I remember this day very clearly,

7954
06:03:40,409 --> 06:03:43,560
because at some point during the day,

7955
06:03:43,560 --> 06:03:44,617
it looked like he wasn't doing super well.

7956
06:03:44,616 --> 06:03:46,979
It looked like the model
wasn't performing super well

7957
06:03:46,979 --> 06:03:48,630
and he was like getting distracted.

7958
06:03:48,630 --> 06:03:49,770
But he actually, it wasn't the case.

7959
06:03:49,770 --> 06:03:53,130
Like what actually happened
was he was trying something new

7960
06:03:53,130 --> 06:03:55,799
where he was just controlling the cursor.

7961
06:03:55,799 --> 06:03:57,930
So he wasn't imagining
moving his hand anymore.

7962
06:03:57,930 --> 06:03:59,970
He was just imagining,
I don't know what it is,

7963
06:03:59,970 --> 06:04:01,050
some like abstract intention

7964
06:04:01,049 --> 06:04:02,729
to move the cursor on the screen.

7965
06:04:02,729 --> 06:04:04,649
And I cannot tell you what the difference

7966
06:04:04,650 --> 06:04:05,610
between those two things are.

7967
06:04:05,610 --> 06:04:06,690
I really truly cannot.

7968
06:04:06,689 --> 06:04:08,039
He's tried to explain it to me before.

7969
06:04:08,040 --> 06:04:12,209
I cannot give a first person
account of what that's like.

7970
06:04:12,209 --> 06:04:14,129
But the expletives that
he uttered in that moment

7971
06:04:14,130 --> 06:04:16,409
were enough to suggest

7972
06:04:16,409 --> 06:04:18,540
that it was a very qualitatively
different experience

7973
06:04:18,540 --> 06:04:22,113
for him to just have direct
neural control over a cursor.

7974
06:04:23,669 --> 06:04:27,869
- I wonder if there's a way through UX

7975
06:04:27,869 --> 06:04:30,869
to encourage a human
being to discover that,

7976
06:04:30,869 --> 06:04:33,663
because he discovered
it, like you said to me,

7977
06:04:33,663 --> 06:04:35,369
that he's a pioneer.

7978
06:04:35,369 --> 06:04:38,819
So he discovered that on
his own through all of this,

7979
06:04:38,819 --> 06:04:42,150
the process of trying to move the cursor

7980
06:04:42,150 --> 06:04:44,280
with different kinds of intentions.

7981
06:04:44,279 --> 06:04:47,369
But that is clearly a really
powerful thing to arrive at,

7982
06:04:47,369 --> 06:04:52,369
which is to let go of trying
to control the fingers

7983
06:04:52,650 --> 06:04:54,930
and the hand and control the actual

7984
06:04:54,930 --> 06:04:56,220
digital device with your mind.

7985
06:04:56,220 --> 06:04:57,810
- That's right, UX is how it works.

7986
06:04:57,810 --> 06:05:00,870
And the ideal UX is one
that the user doesn't

7987
06:05:00,869 --> 06:05:02,890
have to think about what they need to do

7988
06:05:02,890 --> 06:05:04,879
in order to get it done.

7989
06:05:04,879 --> 06:05:05,711
It just does it.

7990
06:05:07,080 --> 06:05:08,040
- That is so fascinating.

7991
06:05:08,040 --> 06:05:11,310
But I wonder on the biological side

7992
06:05:11,310 --> 06:05:13,380
how long it takes for the brain to adapt.

7993
06:05:13,380 --> 06:05:15,720
- Yeah.
- So is it just simply

7994
06:05:15,720 --> 06:05:19,350
learning like high level software,

7995
06:05:19,349 --> 06:05:21,509
or is there like a
neuroplasticity component

7996
06:05:21,509 --> 06:05:25,049
where like the brain is adjusting slowly?

7997
06:05:25,049 --> 06:05:27,809
- Yeah, the truth is, I don't know.

7998
06:05:27,810 --> 06:05:30,180
I'm very excited to see with
sort of the second participant

7999
06:05:30,180 --> 06:05:34,020
that we implant what the
journey is like for them,

8000
06:05:34,020 --> 06:05:35,700
because we'll have learned a lot more.

8001
06:05:35,700 --> 06:05:37,139
Potentially, we can help them understand

8002
06:05:37,139 --> 06:05:38,152
and explore that direction more quickly.

8003
06:05:38,152 --> 06:05:39,779
This is something I didn't know.

8004
06:05:39,779 --> 06:05:42,479
This wasn't me prompting
Noland to go try this.

8005
06:05:42,479 --> 06:05:44,939
He was just exploring
how to use his device

8006
06:05:44,939 --> 06:05:46,169
and figure it out himself.

8007
06:05:46,169 --> 06:05:48,089
But now that we know that
that's a possibility,

8008
06:05:48,090 --> 06:05:49,560
that maybe there's a way to, for example,

8009
06:05:49,560 --> 06:05:52,290
hint the user, "Don't try
super hard during calibration.

8010
06:05:52,290 --> 06:05:53,850
Just do something that feels natural,

8011
06:05:53,849 --> 06:05:55,680
or just directly control the cursor.

8012
06:05:55,680 --> 06:05:57,420
Don't imagine explicit action."

8013
06:05:57,419 --> 06:05:59,759
And from there, we should be
able to hopefully understand

8014
06:05:59,759 --> 06:06:00,719
how this is for somebody

8015
06:06:00,720 --> 06:06:02,430
who has not experienced that before.

8016
06:06:02,430 --> 06:06:04,229
Maybe that's the default
mode of operation for them.

8017
06:06:04,229 --> 06:06:05,369
You don't have to go through this

8018
06:06:05,369 --> 06:06:07,739
intermediate phase of explicit motions.

8019
06:06:07,740 --> 06:06:10,140
- Or maybe if that naturally
happens for people,

8020
06:06:10,139 --> 06:06:12,779
you can just occasionally encourage them

8021
06:06:12,779 --> 06:06:14,789
to allow themselves to move the cursor.

8022
06:06:14,790 --> 06:06:17,370
Actually sometimes, just
like with a four minute mile,

8023
06:06:17,369 --> 06:06:19,289
just the knowledge that that's possible.

8024
06:06:19,290 --> 06:06:20,580
- Pushes you to do it.

8025
06:06:20,580 --> 06:06:22,469
- Yeah, enables you to do it,

8026
06:06:22,469 --> 06:06:24,000
and then it becomes trivial.

8027
06:06:24,000 --> 06:06:26,094
And then it also makes you wonder,

8028
06:06:26,094 --> 06:06:28,020
it's the cool thing about humans.

8029
06:06:28,020 --> 06:06:31,020
Once there's a lot more
human participants,

8030
06:06:31,020 --> 06:06:32,909
they will discover
things that are possible.

8031
06:06:32,909 --> 06:06:34,590
- Yes, and share their experiences.

8032
06:06:34,590 --> 06:06:35,422
- Yeah, and share.
- With each other.

8033
06:06:35,422 --> 06:06:37,979
- And that because of them sharing it,

8034
06:06:37,979 --> 06:06:39,453
they'll be able to do it.

8035
06:06:40,349 --> 06:06:43,139
All of a sudden, that's
unlocked for everybody,

8036
06:06:43,139 --> 06:06:44,700
because just the knowledge sometimes

8037
06:06:44,700 --> 06:06:46,743
is the thing that enables it to do it.

8038
06:06:46,742 --> 06:06:49,379
- Yeah, I mean, and just
to comment on that too,

8039
06:06:49,380 --> 06:06:51,180
we've probably tried like
a thousand different ways

8040
06:06:51,180 --> 06:06:54,180
to do various aspects of decoding,

8041
06:06:54,180 --> 06:06:55,670
and now we know like what
the right subspace is

8042
06:06:55,669 --> 06:06:56,759
to continue exploring further.

8043
06:06:56,759 --> 06:06:57,626
Again, thanks to Noland

8044
06:06:57,627 --> 06:06:59,516
and the many hours he's put into this.

8045
06:06:59,516 --> 06:07:01,259
And so even just that help,

8046
06:07:01,259 --> 06:07:02,729
like help constraints
sort of the beam search

8047
06:07:02,729 --> 06:07:04,829
of different approaches
that we could explore

8048
06:07:04,830 --> 06:07:07,550
really helps accelerate
for the next person

8049
06:07:07,549 --> 06:07:09,090
the set of things that
we'll get to try on day one,

8050
06:07:09,090 --> 06:07:11,279
how fast we hope to get
them to useful control,

8051
06:07:11,279 --> 06:07:13,469
how fast we can enable 'em
to use it independently,

8052
06:07:13,470 --> 06:07:14,630
and to get value out of the system.

8053
06:07:14,630 --> 06:07:16,979
So yeah, massive hats off to Noland

8054
06:07:16,979 --> 06:07:19,290
and all the participants
that came before him

8055
06:07:19,290 --> 06:07:20,880
to make this technology a reality.

8056
06:07:20,880 --> 06:07:22,920
- So how often are the
updates to the decoder?

8057
06:07:22,919 --> 06:07:24,599
'Cause Noland mentioned like,

8058
06:07:24,599 --> 06:07:26,579
okay, there's a new update
that we're working on,

8059
06:07:26,580 --> 06:07:29,190
and that in the stream, he said

8060
06:07:29,189 --> 06:07:33,449
he plays the snake game
because it's like super hard.

8061
06:07:33,450 --> 06:07:36,450
It's a good way for him to test
like how good the update is.

8062
06:07:37,467 --> 06:07:41,100
And he says like sometimes the
update is a step backwards.

8063
06:07:41,099 --> 06:07:42,932
It's a constant like iteration.

8064
06:07:44,400 --> 06:07:46,050
Like what does the update entail?

8065
06:07:46,049 --> 06:07:48,750
Is it mostly on the decoder side?

8066
06:07:48,750 --> 06:07:49,650
- Yeah, a couple comments.

8067
06:07:49,650 --> 06:07:51,540
So one is it's probably
worth drawing distinction

8068
06:07:51,540 --> 06:07:52,740
between sort of research sessions

8069
06:07:52,740 --> 06:07:54,480
where we're actively
trying different things

8070
06:07:54,479 --> 06:07:56,489
to understand like what
the best approach is

8071
06:07:56,490 --> 06:07:58,700
versus sort of independent
use where we wanted to have

8072
06:07:58,700 --> 06:08:00,360
an ability to just go use the device,

8073
06:08:00,360 --> 06:08:02,490
how anybody would wanna use their MacBook.

8074
06:08:02,490 --> 06:08:04,170
And so what he's referring to is,

8075
06:08:04,169 --> 06:08:05,909
I think usually in the
context of a research session,

8076
06:08:05,909 --> 06:08:08,340
where we're trying many,
many different approaches

8077
06:08:08,340 --> 06:08:09,683
to even unsupervised approaches

8078
06:08:09,683 --> 06:08:10,920
like we talked about earlier

8079
06:08:10,919 --> 06:08:12,539
to try to come up with better ways

8080
06:08:12,540 --> 06:08:14,010
to estimate his true intention

8081
06:08:14,009 --> 06:08:15,689
and more accurately decode it.

8082
06:08:15,689 --> 06:08:18,270
And in those scenarios, I mean we try,

8083
06:08:18,270 --> 06:08:20,069
in any given session, he'll sometimes work

8084
06:08:20,069 --> 06:08:21,479
for like eight hours a day.

8085
06:08:21,479 --> 06:08:23,520
And so that can be hundreds
of different models

8086
06:08:23,520 --> 06:08:24,840
that we would try in that day.

8087
06:08:24,840 --> 06:08:27,330
Like a lot of different things.

8088
06:08:27,330 --> 06:08:29,310
Now, it's also worth noting that we update

8089
06:08:29,310 --> 06:08:30,840
the application he uses quite frequently.

8090
06:08:30,840 --> 06:08:33,389
I think sometimes, up to like
four or five times a day.

8091
06:08:33,389 --> 06:08:35,369
We'll update his application
with different features

8092
06:08:35,369 --> 06:08:37,983
or bug fixes or feedback
that he's given us.

8093
06:08:39,563 --> 06:08:42,674
He's a very articulate person
who is part of the solution.

8094
06:08:42,674 --> 06:08:43,590
He's not a complaining person.

8095
06:08:43,590 --> 06:08:46,049
He says, "Hey, here's this
thing that I've discovered

8096
06:08:46,049 --> 06:08:47,969
is not optimal in my flow.

8097
06:08:47,970 --> 06:08:49,260
Here's some ideas how to fix it.

8098
06:08:49,259 --> 06:08:50,250
Let me know what your thoughts are.

8099
06:08:50,250 --> 06:08:51,990
Let's figure out how to solve it."

8100
06:08:51,990 --> 06:08:54,420
And it often happens that
those things are addressed

8101
06:08:54,419 --> 06:08:57,149
within a couple hours of
him giving us his feedback.

8102
06:08:57,150 --> 06:08:58,257
That's the kind of
iteration cycle we'll have.

8103
06:08:58,257 --> 06:09:00,120
And so sometimes, at the
beginning of the session,

8104
06:09:00,119 --> 06:09:01,658
he'll give us feedback, and
at the end of the session,

8105
06:09:01,658 --> 06:09:03,810
he's giving us feedback
on the next iteration

8106
06:09:03,810 --> 06:09:06,060
of that process or that set up.

8107
06:09:06,060 --> 06:09:07,530
- That's fascinating,
because one of the things

8108
06:09:07,529 --> 06:09:11,039
you mentioned, that there
was 271 pages of notes

8109
06:09:11,040 --> 06:09:14,549
taken from the BCI sessions,
and this was just in March.

8110
06:09:14,549 --> 06:09:17,250
So one of the amazing
things about human beings

8111
06:09:17,250 --> 06:09:20,849
that they can provide,
especially ones who are smart

8112
06:09:20,849 --> 06:09:25,439
and excited and all like positive
and good vibes like Nolan,

8113
06:09:25,439 --> 06:09:27,750
that they can provide
feedback, continuous feedback.

8114
06:09:27,750 --> 06:09:29,369
- Yeah, it also requires,

8115
06:09:29,369 --> 06:09:30,779
just to brag on the team a little bit,

8116
06:09:30,779 --> 06:09:33,389
I work with a lot of exceptional people,

8117
06:09:33,389 --> 06:09:36,149
and it requires the team
being absolutely laser focused

8118
06:09:36,150 --> 06:09:38,730
on the user and what will
be the best for them.

8119
06:09:38,729 --> 06:09:40,926
And it requires like a
level of commitment of,

8120
06:09:40,926 --> 06:09:41,953
"Okay, this is what the user feedback was.

8121
06:09:41,953 --> 06:09:43,350
I have all these meetings.

8122
06:09:43,349 --> 06:09:45,566
We're gonna skip that today
and we're gonna do this."

8123
06:09:45,566 --> 06:09:49,704
That level of focus
commitment is, I would say,

8124
06:09:49,705 --> 06:09:52,680
underappreciated in the world.

8125
06:09:52,680 --> 06:09:54,869
And also, you obviously
have to have the talent

8126
06:09:54,869 --> 06:09:56,969
to be able to execute on
these things effectively.

8127
06:09:56,970 --> 06:10:00,120
And yeah, we have that in loads.

8128
06:10:00,119 --> 06:10:05,069
- Yeah, and this is such a
interesting space of UX design

8129
06:10:05,069 --> 06:10:08,372
because there's so many unknowns here.

8130
06:10:09,419 --> 06:10:13,049
And I can tell UX is difficult

8131
06:10:13,049 --> 06:10:15,362
because of how many people do it poorly.

8132
06:10:17,279 --> 06:10:19,289
It's just not a trivial thing.

8133
06:10:19,290 --> 06:10:20,610
- Yeah, it's also, you know,

8134
06:10:20,610 --> 06:10:23,700
UX is not something that
you can always solve

8135
06:10:23,700 --> 06:10:25,830
by just constant iterating
on different things.

8136
06:10:25,830 --> 06:10:27,180
Like sometimes, you
really need to step back

8137
06:10:27,180 --> 06:10:29,580
and think globally, am
I even in like the right

8138
06:10:29,580 --> 06:10:32,130
sort of minima to be
chasing down for a solution?

8139
06:10:32,130 --> 06:10:33,330
Like there's a lot of problems in which

8140
06:10:33,330 --> 06:10:36,360
sort of fast iteration
cycle is the predictor

8141
06:10:36,360 --> 06:10:37,383
of how successful you will be.

8142
06:10:37,383 --> 06:10:40,950
As a good example, like in
RL simulation, for example,

8143
06:10:40,950 --> 06:10:42,240
the more frequently you get reward,

8144
06:10:42,240 --> 06:10:44,100
the faster you can progress.

8145
06:10:44,099 --> 06:10:44,996
It's just an easier learning prompt,

8146
06:10:44,996 --> 06:10:46,799
the more frequently you get feedback.

8147
06:10:46,799 --> 06:10:47,742
But UX is not that way.

8148
06:10:47,742 --> 06:10:50,399
I mean, users are
actually quite often wrong

8149
06:10:50,400 --> 06:10:52,050
about what the right solution is,

8150
06:10:52,049 --> 06:10:54,779
and it requires a deep understanding
of the technical system

8151
06:10:54,779 --> 06:10:56,069
and what's possible,

8152
06:10:56,069 --> 06:10:58,380
combined with what the problem
is you're trying to solve.

8153
06:10:58,380 --> 06:10:59,610
Not just how the user expressed it,

8154
06:10:59,610 --> 06:11:01,770
but what the true underlying problem is

8155
06:11:01,770 --> 06:11:04,080
to actually get to the right place.

8156
06:11:04,080 --> 06:11:05,580
- Yeah, that's the old like stories

8157
06:11:05,580 --> 06:11:08,193
of Steve Jobs like rolling in there, like,

8158
06:11:09,090 --> 06:11:11,459
yeah, the user is a useful signal,

8159
06:11:11,459 --> 06:11:13,290
but it's not a perfect signal.

8160
06:11:13,290 --> 06:11:15,740
And sometimes, you have to
remove the floppy disk drive

8161
06:11:15,740 --> 06:11:18,840
or whatever the, I forgot
all the crazy stories

8162
06:11:18,840 --> 06:11:23,840
of Steve Jobs like making
wild design decisions.

8163
06:11:24,270 --> 06:11:27,153
But there, some of it is aesthetic,

8164
06:11:29,250 --> 06:11:33,810
that some of it is about the
love you put into the design,

8165
06:11:33,810 --> 06:11:36,783
which is very much a Steve
Jobs-Jony Ive type of thing.

8166
06:11:38,340 --> 06:11:41,610
But when you have a human
being using their brain

8167
06:11:41,610 --> 06:11:45,180
to interact with it, it also
is deeply about function.

8168
06:11:45,180 --> 06:11:46,712
It's not just aesthetic.

8169
06:11:47,669 --> 06:11:50,189
And that you have to empathize

8170
06:11:50,189 --> 06:11:52,500
with a human being before you,

8171
06:11:52,500 --> 06:11:54,962
while not always listening
to them directly.

8172
06:11:55,919 --> 06:11:58,289
Like you have to deeply empathize.

8173
06:11:58,290 --> 06:11:59,880
It's fascinating.

8174
06:11:59,880 --> 06:12:02,010
It's really, really fascinating.

8175
06:12:02,009 --> 06:12:03,750
And at the same time, iterate.

8176
06:12:03,750 --> 06:12:05,310
But not iterate in small ways.

8177
06:12:05,310 --> 06:12:08,940
Sometimes, a complete like
rebuilding the design.

8178
06:12:08,939 --> 06:12:10,529
He said that,

8179
06:12:10,529 --> 06:12:13,079
Noland said in the early
days, the UX sucked.

8180
06:12:13,080 --> 06:12:14,730
But you improved quickly.

8181
06:12:14,729 --> 06:12:16,470
What was that journey like?

8182
06:12:16,470 --> 06:12:19,050
- Yeah, I mean, I'll give
one concrete example.

8183
06:12:19,049 --> 06:12:22,139
So he really wanted to
be able to read manga.

8184
06:12:22,139 --> 06:12:23,880
This is something that he, I mean,

8185
06:12:23,880 --> 06:12:25,132
it sounds like a simple thing,

8186
06:12:25,132 --> 06:12:26,757
but it's actually a
really big deal for him.

8187
06:12:26,757 --> 06:12:28,800
And he couldn't do it
with his mouth stick.

8188
06:12:28,799 --> 06:12:29,729
It wasn't accessible.

8189
06:12:29,729 --> 06:12:32,579
You can't scroll with a
mouse stick on his iPad

8190
06:12:32,580 --> 06:12:34,200
on the website that he
